# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: leeds
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] The **Chapeltown Riots of 1981** took place in the Leeds district of Chapeltown in West Yorkshire, England, during a time when many other areas of the UK were suffering similar problems (such as London, Birmingham and Liverpool).
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] The riots unfolded in July 1981 from a background of racial tension, inner city poverty, poor housing and high unemployment (which was rising rapidly as a result of the recession at the time).
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] This brought high tension, particularly amongst the area's Caribbean community, culminating in attacks on the local police.
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] The *Yorkshire Evening Post* reported on the events from a 'law and order' perspective, quoting police and council sources.
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] The *Leeds Other Paper* reported on the social and community aspects of the disturbances, including the root causes.
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] These were not to be the last riots in the area.
[src:leeds/1981-chapeltown-riots] In 1987 there was further rioting in Chapeltown and in 2001 there was widespread rioting in nearby Harehills.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] The **Chapeltown riots** **of 1987** took place in the Leeds district of Chapeltown in West Yorkshire, England.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] Widespread rioting in Chapeltown also occurred in 1975 and 1981.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] During the 1981 riots, rioting took place not only in Chapeltown, but also in London, Birmingham and Liverpool.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] The riots of 1987 began on Sunday, 21 June, when a black teenager, 17 year old Marcus Skellington, was arrested and beaten by police.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] It is estimated that 70 teenagers participated in smashing shop windows, looting and attacking police officers 22 and 21 June.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] On 23 June, shops, cars, and windows were burned, bombed and stoned, including a sex shop which was completely burnt down.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] The burning of the sex shop was particularly significant for two reasons.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] First, it was not widely supported or wanted by the local community and had been protested prior to the riots.
[src:leeds/1987-chapeltown-riot] Second, it was believed that the police carried out surveillance of the Hayfield Pub car park for marijuana dealing from above the sex shop, despite the sex shop operating illegally at times.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The **1996 UEFA European Football Championship**, commonly referred to as **Euro 96**, was the 10th UEFA European Championship, a quadrennial football tournament contested by European nations and organised by UEFA.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] It took place in England from 8 to 30 June 1996.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] It was the first European Championship to feature 16 finalists, following UEFA's decision to expand the tournament from eight teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Matches were staged in eight cities and, although not all games were sold out, the tournament holds the European Championship's second-highest aggregate attendance (1,276,000) and average per game (41,158) for the 16-team format, surpassed only in 2012.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Germany won the tournament, beating the Czech Republic 2–1 in the final with a golden goal from Oliver Bierhoff during extra time; this was the first major competition to be decided using this method.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] This was also Germany's first major title won as a unified nation, adding to the two European Championship titles won by West Germany prior to reunification.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] At the time of the bidding process, it had not yet been confirmed that 16 teams would be participating.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Instead, the bids were largely prepared as if hosting an eight-team tournament, meaning only four venues were due to be required.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] All candidates had to submit their plans by 10 December 1991.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The hosting of the event was contested by five bids: Austria, England, Greece, the Netherlands and Portugal.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The English bid was selected by the UEFA Executive Committee at a meeting in Lisbon on 5 May 1992.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] In the year preceding the decision, the English FA had dropped plans to also bid for the 1998 World Cup in order to gain the support of other UEFA members who were planning to bid for that event.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The hosts, England, drew 1–1 with Switzerland in the opening match of Group A when Alan Shearer's 23rd-minute goal was cancelled out by a late Kubilay Türkyilmaz penalty kick.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] England defeated rivals Scotland 2–0 in their next game, and then produced one of their finest performances ever with a 4–1 win over the Netherlands.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Patrick Kluivert's late goal for the Netherlands secured his team second place in the group and ensured that Scotland would exit another major competition on goals scored.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Group B had Western European France and Spain, along with Balkan World Cup participants Romania and Bulgaria.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] France and Spain dominated the group, with France avenging Bulgaria for the 1994 qualification debacle, and World Cup quarter-finalists Romania going home, with no points and only one goal scored.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Groups C and D saw the Czech Republic and Croatia, whose national teams had only recently come into existence, qualify for the knockout stage.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The Czechs lost to Germany, the eventual group winners, in their opener, but then defeated Italy and drew with Russia.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Italy's defeat meant they had to beat Germany in their final game to progress, but the World Cup finalists could only manage a 0–0 draw and were eliminated.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] In Group D, Croatia qualified for the quarter-finals, with wins over Turkey (1–0) and Denmark (3–0).
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The loss to the Croats ultimately sent the Danes, the surprise champions of 1992, home.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Turkey became the first team since the introduction of a group stage to be eliminated without gaining a point or scoring a goal.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The other three quarter-finalists were Portugal (whose "Golden Generation" was competing at its first major tournament), Spain, and a France team featuring a young Zinedine Zidane.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The knockout stage was characterised by negative, defensive play; as a result, only nine goals were scored in the seven games and four of the matches were decided on penalties.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The first quarter-final between the hosts and Spain ended goalless, after Spain had two goals disallowed and two claims for a penalty denied.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The English progressed 4–2 on spot kicks.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] France and the Netherlands also played out a 0–0 draw, with France winning the penalty shootout 5–4.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Jürgen Klinsmann opened the scoring for Germany in their match against Croatia.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] A goal from Davor Šuker evened the score after 51 minutes, before Matthias Sammer of Germany scored eight minutes later, and the game ended 2–1 to Germany.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The Czech Republic progressed after beating Portugal 1–0.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The first semi-final, featuring France and the Czech Republic, resulted in another 0–0 draw and penalties.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Reynald Pedros was the one player to miss in the shootout, as the Czechs won the penalty shoot-out 6–5.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The other semi-final was a repeat of the 1990 World Cup semi-final between Germany and England.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Alan Shearer headed in after three minutes to give his side the lead, but Stefan Kuntz evened the score less than 15 minutes later, and the score remained 1–1 after 90 minutes.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] In extra time, Paul Gascoigne came very close to scoring a golden goal, but fractionally missed a cross from Shearer in front of the empty goal, Darren Anderton hit the post, and Kuntz had a goal disallowed for pushing.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Neither team was able to find a second goal.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] In penalties, both sides scored their first five kicks, but in the sixth round, Gareth Southgate had his penalty saved, allowing Andreas Möller to score the winning goal.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The final saw the Czech Republic hoping to repeat Euro 1976 when Czechoslovakia defeated West Germany; the Germans were aiming to win their third European Championship.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Patrik Berger scored from a penalty in 59th minute to put the Czechs ahead.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] German substitute Oliver Bierhoff scored in the 73rd minute to make it 1–1.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Five minutes into extra time, Bierhoff's shot was mishandled by Czech goalkeeper Kouba and the ball ended up in the back of the net for the first golden goal in the history of the competition.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Germany were European champions again, but for the first time as a unified country.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] On 30 November 1992, UEFA formally decided to expand the tournament to sixteen teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] UEFA cited the increased number of international teams following the dissolution of the Soviet Union and of Yugoslavia – rising from 33 UEFA members in 1988 to 48 by 1994 – as a driving factor behind the expansion.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] 47 teams eventually entered to compete for the fifteen remaining places in the finals, alongside hosts England.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The draw for the qualifying competition took place in Manchester on 22 January 1994.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The teams were divided into eight groups, each containing either six or five teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The qualifying process began in April 1994 and concluded in December 1995.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] At the end of the qualifying group stage in November 1995, the eight group winners qualified automatically, along with the six highest-ranked second-placed teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The remaining two second-placed teams, the Netherlands and the Republic of Ireland, contested a one-off play-off match in England to decide the final qualifier.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] With the extended format, three teams qualified for their first European Championship: Bulgaria, Switzerland, and Turkey.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Seven of the eight participants at the previous tournament in 1992 were again present, with only Sweden – despite also having finished third in the World Cup two years earlier – missing out.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Italy and Spain qualified after missing out Euro 1992 and Romania and Portugal after 12 years.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] From 1960 to 1988, Russia competed as the Soviet Union, and in 1992 as CIS.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] From 1972 to 1988, Germany competed as West Germany.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] From 1960 to 1980, the Czech Republic competed as Czechoslovakia.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The draw for the final tournament took place on 17 December 1995 at the International Convention Centre in Birmingham.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Only four teams were seeded: England (as hosts), Denmark (as holders), Spain and Germany (as the two highest ranked teams).
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The remaining twelve teams were all unseeded and could be drawn in any group.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Automatically selected as a top-seeded team into pot 1, irrespective of their ranking position.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Defending champions Denmark were automatically assigned to Pot 1, and could be drawn into group position B1, C1 or D1.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The team drawn first from each group bowl was placed into position 4 in their group; the team drawn second in position 3; and the team drawn third in position 2.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Finally, the four top-seeded teams were drawn from the separate Pot 1 bowl, and placed consecutively into position 1 of each group bowl.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The balls were drawn by UEFA figures Gerhard Aigner and Lennart Johansson.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Since the implementation of the Taylor Report in 1990, following the 1989 Hillsborough stadium disaster, England now had enough all-seater stadia of sufficient capacity to hold an expanded tournament due to the necessary stadium refurbishment by its leading clubs.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The stadium capacities listed in the table are for the time of the tournament.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Each national team had to submit a squad of 22 players, three of whom must be goalkeepers.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] To accommodate the expansion from an 8-team finals tournament to 16 teams, the format was changed from that used in 1992 with the addition of two extra groups in the group stage, and an extra round in the knockout phases.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The four groups (A to D) still contained four teams each, with the top two from each group still going through to the knockout phase.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] 8 teams then went into the new quarter-finals, ahead of the usual semi-finals and final, with 8 teams going out at the group stage.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The format is exactly the one which was applied to the 1958, 1962, 1966 and 1970 World Cups, except for the absence of a third place play-off.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] A custom version of the Adidas Questra, the *Questra Europa*, was the official match ball of the championships.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The design of the ball included a reworking of the England badge, and was the first coloured ball in a major football tournament.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Match officials are listed in the two collapsed tables below.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The teams finishing in the top two positions in each of the four groups progress to the quarter-finals, while the bottom two teams in each group were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] For the first time at a European Championship three points were awarded for a win, with one for a draw and a none for a defeat.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] For the first time in the history of the European Championship, the position of teams tied on points was decided by their head-to-head record, and not goal difference.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] If, after having applied criteria 1 to 3 to more than two teams, two teams still have an equal ranking, criteria 1 to 3 are reapplied exclusively to the matches between the two teams in question to determine the final rankings of the two teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Position using UEFA's national team coefficient ranking system calculated using average points per game from: the Euro 1992 qualifying stage and final tournament, the 1994 World Cup qualifying stage and final tournament and the Euro 1996 qualifying stage.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The knockout stage was a single-elimination tournament with each round eliminating the losers.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Any game that was undecided by the end of the regular 90 minutes, was followed by up to thirty minutes of extra time.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] For the first time in a major football competition, the golden goal system was applied, whereby the first team to score during the extra time would become the winner.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] If no goal was scored there would be a penalty shoot-out to determine the winner.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] For the first time the final was won by a golden goal.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] As with every tournament since UEFA Euro 1984, there was no third place play-off.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] There were 64 goals scored in 31 matches, for an average of 2.06 goals per match.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Alan Shearer was awarded the Golden Boot award, after scoring five goals in the group stage and in the semi-finals against Germany.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The competition slogan was **Football Comes Home** reflecting that the sport's rules were first standardised in the United Kingdom.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] UEFA President Lennart Johansson had said that the organisation had felt it was time to bring the event "back to the motherland of football".
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The slogan was incorporated into the competition's most popular song: "Three Lions" recorded by comedians David Baddiel and Frank Skinner with Britpop band the Lightning Seeds.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Baddiel and Skinner were then strongly connected with football owing to their BBC show *Fantasy Football League*.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Released as a single, the song topped the UK Singles Chart for a total of two weeks.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] It was promoted by a video featuring the England squad.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The song was prominently sung by England fans during all their games, and was also chanted by the German team upon parading the trophy in Berlin after the tournament.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] "Three Lions" was the official song of the England team, and is the song most strongly connected with the tournament, however the official song of the tournament was "We're in This Together" by Simply Red.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The song was performed at the tournament's opening ceremony.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The British Royal Mint issued a commemorative £2 coin in 1996, which featured a representation of a football, "1996" in the centre, and 16 small rings representing the 16 competing teams.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Further special coins were only issued in the Isle of Man and Gibraltar.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The official mascot, 'Goaliath', was designed in a similar fashion to the original World Cup mascot from the 1966 World Cup.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Goaliath comprised a lion, the image on the English team crest, dressed in an England football strip and football boots whilst holding a football under his right arm.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] A video game tie-in was developed by Gremlin Interactive for Windows, MS-DOS, and the Sega Saturn.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The Saturn version was the subject of considerable media hype and was a major system-seller for the system in the United Kingdom.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] A terrorist attack took place in Manchester on 15 June, one day before the group stage match between Germany and Russia was due to take place in the same city.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The detonation of a van bomb in the city centre injured 212 people and caused an estimated £700 million worth of damage.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Four days after the blast, the Provisional Irish Republican Army issued a statement in which it claimed responsibility, but regretted causing injury to civilians.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The Manchester bombing was the first and so far only major terrorist attack in the host city of an ongoing UEFA European Championship.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The scheduled match at Old Trafford on the day following the bombing went ahead as planned after the stadium had been heavily guarded overnight and carefully searched; the game, in which Germany defeated Russia 3–0, was watched by a near capacity crowd of 50,700.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The aggregate attendance of 1,276,000 and average attendance of 41,158 per game were the highest for the European Championship (in its 16-team format) until the 2012 tournament.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] However, these numbers were based on the number of tickets sold rather than the number of spectators in the ground, which was often significantly lower.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] After England's defeat to Germany in the semi-finals, a large-scale riot took place in Trafalgar Square and the surrounding area.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Further outbreaks of trouble occurred in the streets of several other towns.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] The police and German-made cars were targeted, with damage also caused to various other properties.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] A Russian student was stabbed in Brighton after attackers mistook him for being German.
[src:leeds/1996-european-football-championship] Despite this outbreak, the tournament overall was free of hooliganism, helping rehabilitate England's reputation after their fans' conduct during the previous decades.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The **2014 Tour de France** was the 101st edition of the race, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The 3,660.5-kilometre (2,274.5 mi) race included 21 stages, starting in Leeds, Yorkshire, United Kingdom, on 5 July and finishing on the Champs-Élysées in Paris on 27 July.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The race also visited Belgium for part of a stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Vincenzo Nibali of the Astana team won the overall general classification by more than seven minutes, the biggest winning margin since 1997.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] By winning, he had acquired victories in all Grand Tours.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Jean-Christophe Péraud (Ag2r–La Mondiale) placed second, with Thibaut Pinot (FDJ.fr) third.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Marcel Kittel of Giant–Shimano was the first rider to wear the general classification leader's yellow jersey after winning stage one.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] He lost the following day to stage winner Nibali as the race reached the mountains.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali held the race lead until the end of the ninth stage, when it was taken by Lotto–Belisol's Tony Gallopin.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The yellow jersey returned to Nibali the following stage, and he held it until the conclusion of the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The points classification was decided early in the race and was won by Cannondale's Peter Sagan.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Rafał Majka of Tinkoff–Saxo, winner of two mountain stages, won the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The team classification was won by Ag2r–La Mondiale and Alessandro De Marchi (Cannondale) was given the award for the most combative rider.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Kittel and Nibali won the most stages, with four each.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Following criticism by the professional women's peloton and campaign groups like Le Tour Entier regarding the lack of a women's Tour de France, a one day women's race – La Course by Le Tour de France – was held on the Champs-Élysées, prior to the last stage of the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Twenty-two teams participated in the 2014 edition of the Tour de France.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The race was the 18th of the 29 events in the UCI World Tour, and all of its eighteen UCI ProTeams were automatically invited, and obliged, to attend the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] On 28 January 2014, the organiser of the Tour, Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), announced the four second-tier UCI Professional Continental teams given wildcard invitations: Cofidis, Bretagne–Séché Environnement, IAM Cycling and NetApp–Endura.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The team presentation – where the members of each team's roster are introduced in front of the media and local dignitaries – took place at the First Direct Arena in Leeds, United Kingdom, on 3 July, two days before the opening stage held in the city.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The riders arrived at the arena by a ceremonial ride from the University of Leeds.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The event included performances from Embrace and Opera North, in front of an audience of 10,000.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Each squad was allowed a maximum of nine riders, therefore the start list contained a total of 198 riders.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Of these, 47 were riding the Tour de France for the first time.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The riders came from 34 countries; France, Spain, Italy, Netherlands, Germany, Australia and Belgium all had 10 or more riders in the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Giant–Shimano's Ji Cheng was the first Chinese rider to participate in the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Riders from eight countries won stages during the race; German riders won the largest number of stages, with seven.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The average age of riders in the race was 29.88 years, ranging from the 20-year-old Danny van Poppel to the 42-year-old Jens Voigt, both Trek Factory Racing riders.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Voigt, riding in his final year as a professional, equalled Stuart O'Grady's record for most appearances in the Tour with 17.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Garmin–Sharp had the highest average age, while Trek Factory Racing had the lowest.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] pre-race favourites; both were forced to abandon the race due to injuries caused by crashes.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] According to many observers before the race the top two favourites for the general classification were Chris Froome (Team Sky) and Alberto Contador (Tinkoff–Saxo).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Their closest rivals were thought to have been Vincenzo Nibali (Astana) and Alejandro Valverde (Movistar Team).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] A possible contender was the 2013 Tour runner-up, Nairo Quintana, who had chosen not to ride the Tour after his 2014 Giro d'Italia win that took place during May.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Andy Schleck (Trek Factory Racing), who was retroactively awarded the 2010 Tour title, was selected by his team as a domestique, and was not considered a possible favourite.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The other riders considered contenders for the general classification were Andrew Talansky (Garmin–Sharp), Rui Costa (Lampre–Merida), Thibaut Pinot (FDJ.fr), Tejay van Garderen (BMC Racing Team) and Jurgen Van den Broeck (Lotto–Belisol).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Defending champion and runner-up in the 2012 Tour, Froome, had shown his form so far in the 2014 season by winning the general classification of two stage races, the Tour of Oman and the Tour de Romandie.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Contador, winner of the 2007 and 2009 Tours, also won two stage races, the Tirreno–Adriatico and the Tour of the Basque Country in the lead-up to the Tour, placing second overall in the Volta ao Algarve, Volta a Catalunya and Critérium du Dauphiné.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali had missed the 2013 Tour as he had focused on the 2013 Giro, which he won.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] His highest Tour result was third in 2012.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] His best results so far in the 2014 season were fifth in the Tour de Romandie and seventh in the Dauphiné.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Valverde, who placed eighth in the 2013 Tour and won the 2009 Vuelta a España, had a number of wins in the 2014 season prior to the Tour, most notably, the Vuelta a Andalucía stage race and the La Flèche Wallonne one-day race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Winner of the points classification in the two previous Tours, Sagan, had won the E3 Harelbeke one-day race and won the points classifications in three stage races, the Tirreno–Adriatico, the Tour of California and the Tour de Suisse, during the 2014 season up until the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Cavendish, who won the points classification in 2011, had nine wins so far in the season and had the full backing of his team.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Greipel had amassed a total of twelve wins during the season prior to the Tour, but his team would have to share support for him and Van den Broeck.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Kristoff had won the Milan–San Remo, and was considered a dark horse for the points classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Kittel was seen as a top contender for the bunch sprints, as he won the most stages in the 2013 Tour, a total of four.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] He had an amassed seven wins so far in the season, two of which were in the Giro.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] It was thought that Degenkolb would be used by Giant–Shimano for the more challenging sprints.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] His major results of the season were first place in Gent–Wevelgem and second place in Paris–Roubaix, both one-day races.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] On 14 December 2012, the ASO announced that the English historic county of Yorkshire would host the 2014 edition's early stages (known as the *Grand Départ*).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Further details of the first three stages held in the United Kingdom were released on 17 January 2013.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] This was the fourth Tour to contain stages in the United Kingdom, after 1974, 1994 and 2007.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The entire route was announced by the ASO on 23 October 2013 at the official presentation at the Palais des Congrès in Paris.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] At the event, Stephen Roche, winner of the 1987 Tour, described the route as "fairly soft".
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Notable features of the route were the fifth stage's sections of sett paving, the five high altitude stage finishes and the lack of time trialing, with only stage twenty's 54 km (34 mi) individual time trial.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The first of the two stages held in Yorkshire started in Leeds and finished in Harrogate, with stage two held between York and Sheffield.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] After a transfer to the East Anglian city of Cambridge, the race went south to the finish in London.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The Tour transferred across the English Channel to the start of stage four Le Touquet-Paris-Plage, with the finish in Lille.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage five began in Ypres, Belgium, and finished back in France.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The following three stages crossed the north-east to the Vosges Mountains for stages nine and ten.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The eleventh stage took place between Besançon and Oyonnax through the Jura Mountains.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage twelve headed west to Saint-Étienne, with the next stage moving back east into the Chartreuse Mountains, with the finish at the Alpine ski resort of Chamrousse.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The fourteenth stage ended in the town of Risoul.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The following stage took the race south to Nîmes.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] After a transfer to Carcassonne, the route moved into the Pyrenees for the next two stages.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The nineteenth stage took a northerly direction to the department of Dordogne and the location of stage twenty.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] A long transfer took the Tour back to the north-east to finish with the Champs-Élysées stage in Paris.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] There were 21 stages in the race, covering a total distance of 3,660.5 km (2,275 mi).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The longest mass-start stage was the seventh at 234.5 km (146 mi), and stage 17 was the shortest at 124.5 km (77 mi).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nine stages were officially classified as flat, five as medium mountain and six as high mountain.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage five, although classified as medium mountain, was flat with sett paving sections.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] There were five summit finishes: stage 10, to La Planche des Belles Filles; stage 13, to Chamrousse; stage 14, to Risoul; stage 17, to Saint-Lary Pla d’Adet; and stage 18, to Hautacam.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was the 2,360 m (7,740 ft)-high Col d'Izoard mountain pass on stage fourteen.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] It was among six *hors catégorie* (English: beyond category) rated climbs in the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] There were nine new stage start or finish locations.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The rest days were after stage 10, in the Besançon, and after 15, in Carcassonne.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The first stage's bunch sprint finish was won by Marcel Kittel.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] A crash in the sprint caused Mark Cavendish, a favourite for the win, to fall; he did not start stage two.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Kittel gained the race leader's yellow jersey and the green jersey as the leader of the points classification, with Jens Voigt taking the polka dot jersey as the leader of the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In the following stage, likened to a "mini Liège-Bastogne-Liège", Vincenzo Nibali took the stage win and yellow jersey, attacking on Sheffield's hilly terrain with 2 km (1.2 mi) remaining.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Peter Sagan took the green jersey and Cyril Lemoine (Cofidis) took the polka dot jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stages three and four, finishing in London and Lille respectively, ended in bunch sprints and were both won by Kittel.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Crashes in stages four and five forced pre-race favourite Chris Froome to abandon the race; his injuries were later revealed to be fractures to his left wrist and right hand.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The weather was wet throughout the fifth stage, with the sett paving causing many crashes (although not Froome's).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The fractured ending was won by an attack in the final 5 km (3.1 mi) by Lars Boom of Belkin Pro Cycling.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali, who placed third, extended his overall lead over his rivals, with Alberto Contador 2 min 37 s down.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] André Greipel won stage six's bunch sprint in Reims.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Another bunch sprint took place at the end of the next stage, with the hilly finish decided by a photo finish between Sagan and the winner Matteo Trentin (Omega Pharma–Quick-Step).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage eight, the first at altitude, was taken by Ag2r–La Mondiale's Blel Kadri, who attacked from a breakaway group with 25 km (15.5 mi) to go; he managed to hold his lead over the chasing group of overall favourites, who came in over two minutes behind.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] His win put Kadri into the polka dot jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Another solo victory came the following day, when Tony Martin of Omega Pharma–Quick-Step dropped fellow breakaway rider Alessandro De Marchi (Cannondale) with 60 km (37.3 mi) remaining.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] A large group that formed in pursuit of the duo finished 2 min 45 s behind, with the unconcerned general classification contenders coming together in at 7 min 46 s down.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The yellow jersey went to a rider from the first group, Lotto–Belisol's Tony Gallopin.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Martin now led the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage ten was the Tour's first high mountain stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] On the final climb to the finish at La Planche des Belles Filles, Nibali attacked from the group of overall contenders with 3 km (1.9 mi) remaining, passed two surviving riders from the day's early breakaway, and claimed his second stage win, which put him back in the yellow jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Joaquim Rodríguez (Team Katusha), one of the two breakaway riders, took the polka dot jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Contador crashed during the descent of the Petit Ballon, 95 km (59.0 mi) into the stage, forcing him to quit the race; it was later revealed that he had fractured his right tibia.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The next day was the first rest day of the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Stage eleven's rolling terrain resulted in a final peloton that included mainly puncheurs; Gallopin won the stage after an attack 13 km (8.1 mi) from the finish in Oyonnax split the peloton and a second with 2.7 km (1.7 mi) remaining that successfully held off the chasers.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The twelfth stage was won by Alexander Kristoff from a bunch sprint.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali took the stage win the following stage, making his move from the leading group in the final 3 km (1.9 mi) on the *hors catégorie* climb to Chamrousse.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] He extended his lead over the second-placed overall rider Alejandro Valverde to 3 min 37 s.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Richie Porte, who was second overall before the stage and the new leader of Team Sky, lost around nine minutes and dropped to sixteenth.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali took the lead of the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In stage fourteen, Rafał Majka (Tinkoff–Saxo) attacked from a reduced breakaway on the climb to the finish in Risoul with 10 km (6.2 mi) remaining and managed to hold off chasing the group of overall favourites and soloed to victory.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali, second in the stage, extended his lead further by one minute as Valverde lost time and Rodríguez regained the polka dot jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Kristoff won the bunch sprint in the transitional stage fifteen.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In the first of the three stages in the Pyrenees, the sixteenth, a breakaway group of 21 riders formed 75 km (46.6 mi) in.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The group reduced to five after the final climb, the *hors catégorie* Port de Balès with 21 km (13.0 mi) remaining, out of which came the winner, Michael Rogers of (Tinkoff–Saxo), who attacked 3 km (1.9 mi) from finish in Bagnères-de-Luchon.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The group of general classification favourites came in over eight minutes down.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The Tour's queen stage, the seventeenth, featured three first-category climbs and the *hors catégorie* climb to the finish at Saint-Lary Pla d’Adet.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] An early nine-strong breakaway was pulled back before the first climb by Team Katusha for their rider Rodríguez to take the mountains classification points and the temporary lead of the competition.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] This led to the formation of a large lead group which gradually split across the middle climbs.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Rodriguez and Majka led the lead group race over the penultimate climb, with the former first.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] On the final climb, a group of four that had escaped were caught by Majka, who had dropped Rodríguez, and he soloed to claim his second stage win and the large number of points for the summit finish.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali had split apart the group of chasing overall favourites and came in third.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Second-placed overall Valverde lost a minute to Thibaut Pinot in third.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The Tour's final mountain stage, the eighteenth, saw Nibali take his fourth victory of the race at Hautacam; his stage winning move came 9 km (5.6 mi) from the finish, on the climb to Hautacam.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] He finished 1 min 10 s ahead of a group which were four of his nearest general classification rivals, with the exception of Valverde, who lost further time and dropped to fourth overall, displaced by Thibaut Pinot and Jean-Christophe Péraud, respectively.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Majka finished third in the stage and secured the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In stage nineteen, Ramūnas Navardauskas of Garmin–Sharp attacked a peloton fractured by rain 13 km (8.1 mi) from the finish to win the stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Martin claimed his second stage of the Tour in the penultimate stage's individual time trial.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] His time of 1h 6 min 21 s over the 54 km (33.6 mi) course was 1 min 39 s faster than second-placed Tom Dumoulin (Giant–Shimano).
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali finished fourth, increasing his advantage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In the final stage, Kittel secured a second successive victory on the Champs-Élysées in Paris, his fourth stage win of the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Nibali finished the race to win the general classification by a margin of 7 min 39 s, the largest winning margin since Jan Ullrich in the 1997 Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Second and third respectively were Péraud and Pinot, with the latter 8 min 15 s down on Nibali.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The points classification was won by Sagan with 431 points; Kristoff came second with 282 points.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Majka finished with 181 points in the mountains classification, 13 ahead of second-placed Nibali.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Pinot was the best young rider, with Romain Bardet (Ag2r–La Mondiale) second.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The team classification was won by Ag2r–La Mondiale, 34 min 46 s ahead of second-placed Belkin Pro Cycling.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Of the 198 starters, 164 reached the finish of the last stage in Paris.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] There were four main individual classifications contested in the 2014 Tour de France, as well as a team competition.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, which was calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] There were no time bonuses given at the end of stages for this edition of the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] If a crash had happened within the final 3 km (1.9 mi) of a stage, not including the time trial and summit finishes, the riders involved would have received the same time as the group they were in when the crash occurred.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The rider with the lowest cumulative time was the winner of the general classification and was considered the overall winner of the Tour.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The rider leading the classification wore a yellow jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The second classification was the points classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Riders received points for finishing among the highest placed in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints during the stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The points available for each stage finish were determined by the stage's type.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The leader was identified by a green jersey.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The third classification was the mountains classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit of the most difficult climbs first.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second-, first-category and *hors catégorie*, with the more difficult climbs rated lower.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Double points were awarded on the summit finishes on stages 10, 13, 14, 17 and 18.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The leader wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The final individual classification was the young rider classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] This was calculated the same way as the general classification, but the classification was restricted to riders who were born on or after 1 January 1989.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The final classification was a team classification.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] This was calculated using the finishing times of the best three riders per team on each stage; the leading team was the team with the lowest cumulative time.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The number of stage victories and placings per team determined the outcome of a tie.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that lead this classification were identified with yellow number bibs on the back of their jerseys and yellow helmets.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each stage to the rider considered, by a jury, to have "made the greatest effort and who has demonstrated the best qualities of sportsmanship".
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] No combativity awards were given for the time trial and the final stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The winner wore a red number bib the following stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] At the conclusion of the Tour, Alessandro De Marchi won the overall super-combativity award, again, decided by a jury.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] A total of €2,035,000 was awarded in cash prizes in the race.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The overall winner of the general classification received €450,000, with the second and third placed riders got €200,000 and €100,000 respectively.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] All finishers of the race were awarded with money.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The holders of the classifications benefited on each stage they led; the final winners of the points and mountains were given €25,000, while the best young rider and most combative rider got €20,000.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The winners of the team classification received €50,000.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Joaquim Rodríguez won the Henri Desgrange and Blel Kadri won the Jacques Goddet.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Riders from the ProTeams competing individually, as well as for their teams and nations, for points that contributed towards the World Tour rankings.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Points were awarded to the top twenty finishers in the general classification and to the top five finishers in each stage.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] The 200 points accrued by Vincenzo Nibali moved him from fortieth position to second in the individual ranking.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Movistar Team retained their lead of the team ranking, ahead of second-placed Ag2r–La Mondiale.
[src:leeds/2014-tour-de-france] Spain remained as leaders of the nation ranking, with Italy second.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] The **2015 Leeds City Council election** took place on Thursday 7 May 2015 to elect members of Leeds City Council in England.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] It was held on the same day as the 2015 general election and other local elections across the UK.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] As per the election cycle, one third of the council's seats were up for election.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] The councillors subsequently elected replaced those elected when their individual seats were previously contested in 2011.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] No political party gained or lost any seats and the Labour Party retained all 22 of their contested council seats and their majority control of the council since 2011.
[src:leeds/2015-leeds-city-council-election] The electoral division results listed below are based on the changes from the 2011 elections, not taking into account any mid-term by-elections or party defections.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] The **2016 Leeds City Council election** took place on Thursday 5 May 2016 to elect members of Leeds City Council in England.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] It was on the same day as other local elections.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] The councillors subsequently elected replaced those elected when their individual seats were previously contested in 2012.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] The Labour Party retained all 21 of their contested council seats, maintaining their majority control of the council with a total of 63 of the 99 elected councillors.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] It was the second election in a row in which no party gained or lost any seats.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] Incumbent Labour councillors, Debra Coupar (Cross Gates & Whinmoor), Roger Harington (Gipton & Harehills) and Janette Walker (Headingley), all stood for new wards.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] Coupar was elected to represent Temple Newsam and Walker replaced Coupar as a councillor for Cross Gates & Whinmoor.
[src:leeds/2016-leeds-city-council-election] Harington lost to the Liberal Democrats in Weetwood.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro was announced as the host city at the 121st IOC Session in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 2 October 2009.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] 11,238 athletes from 207 nations took part in the 2016 Games, including first-time entrants Kosovo, South Sudan, and the Refugee Olympic Team.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] With 306 sets of medals, the Games featured 28 Olympic sports, including rugby sevens and golf, which were added to the Olympic program in 2009.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] These sporting events took place at 33 venues in the host city and at five separate venues in the Brazilian cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, Salvador, Brasília, and Manaus.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] These were also the first Summer Olympics to take place under the International Olympic Committee (IOC) presidency of Thomas Bach.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The games were opened by acting president of Brazil (and later president), Michel Temer and closed by Bach.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table, winning the most gold medals (46) and the highest number of medals overall (121); the U.S. team also won its 1,000th Summer Olympic gold medal.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Great Britain finished second and the only country to increase its tally of medals in the Summer Olympiad immediately after being the host nation.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil won seven gold medals and 19 total medals, its best result at any Olympics, finishing in thirteenth place.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Bahrain, Fiji, Ivory Coast, Jordan, Kosovo, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Tajikistan, and Vietnam all won their first gold medals, as did the group of Independent Olympic Athletes (from Kuwait).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The bidding process for the 2016 Summer Olympics was officially launched on 16 May 2007.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The first step for each city was to submit an initial application to the International Olympic Committee by 13 September 2007, confirming their intention to bid.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Completed official bid files containing answers to a 25-question IOC form were to be submitted by each city by the deadline of 14 January 2008.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] On 4 June 2008, two months before the Beijing Olympics, four candidate cities were chosen for the shortlist: Chicago, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, and Tokyo, which had already hosted the Summer Olympics in 1964.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Three cities—Baku, Doha, and Prague—failed to reach the candidature phase.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Nawal El Moutawakel of Morocco headed the 10-member Evaluation Commission, having also chaired the evaluation commission for the 2012 Summer Olympics bids, which was awarded to London, United Kingdom.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The commission made on-site inspections in the second quarter of 2009.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] They issued a comprehensive technical appraisal for IOC members on 2 September, one month before the elections.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Many safeguards were put in place to prevent bidding cities from communicating with or directly influencing the 115 IOC members eligible to vote in the elections.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] For example, cities could not invite any IOC member to visit, nor could they send anything that could be construed as a gift.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Nonetheless, bidding cities invested large sums in their PR and media programs to indirectly influence the IOC members by garnering domestic support and backing from sports media and general international media.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The final voting was held in Copenhagen on 2 October 2009, with Madrid and Rio de Janeiro considered favorites to secure the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Chicago was eliminated after the first round of voting, and Tokyo after the second (The latter city would eventually be awarded the 2020 Summer Olympics in 2013).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro took a significant lead over Madrid, heading into the final round; the lead was held, and Rio de Janeiro was announced as host of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] On 26 June 2011, it was reported on Around The Rings that Roderlei Generali, the COO of the Rio de Janeiro Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games, resigned just one year after taking the job at ROOC.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] This came just five months after CCO Flávio Pestana quit for personal reasons.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Pestana withdrew later during the 2012 Summer Paralympics, and Renato Ciuchin was then appointed as COO.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Events took place at eighteen existing venues, nine new venues constructed specifically for the Games, and seven temporary venues.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] For the events held in Rio de Janeiro, each event was held in one of four geographically segregated Olympic clusters–Barra, Copacabana, Deodoro, and Maracanã–as was done for the 2007 Pan American Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Several of the venues were located at the Barra Cluster Olympic Park.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Nearly half of the athletes could reach their venues in less than 10 minutes, and almost 75 per cent could do so in less than 25 minutes.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Of the 34 competition venues, eight underwent some permanent works, seven were totally temporary and nine were constructed as permanent legacy venues.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The largest venue at the Games in terms of seating capacity was the 75,000-seat Maracanã Stadium, which served as the ceremonies venue and site of the football finals.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The second largest stadium was the 60,000-seat Estádio Olímpico Nilton Santos (formerly João Havelange during the Games), which hosted track and field events.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The athletes' village was said to be the largest in Olympic history.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Barra Olympic Park is a cluster of nine sporting venues in Barra da Tijuca, in the west zone of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The site was formerly occupied by the Autódromo Internacional Nelson Piquet, also known as the Jacarepaguá Formula One circuit.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As well as the Estádio Olímpico João Havelange and Maracanã and in Rio de Janeiro, football matches took place at five venues in the cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, and the more distant Salvador, Brasília and Manaus.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Rio's historical downtown underwent an urban waterfront revitalization project known as *Porto Maravilha*, covering 5 km2 (1.9 mi2) in area.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The project aimed to redevelop the port area, increase the city center's attractiveness, and enhance Rio's competitive position in the global economy.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The urban renovation involved 700 km (430 mi) of public networks for water supply, sanitation, drainage, electricity, gas and telecom; 4 km (2.5 mi) of tunnels; 70 km (43 mi) of roads; 650 km2 (250 mi2) of sidewalks; 17 km (11 mi) of bike path; 15,000 trees; and three sanitation treatment plants.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As part of this renovation, a new tram was built from the Santos Dumont Airport to Rodoviária Novo Rio, due to open in April 2016.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Games required over 200 kilometers of security fencing.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A 15,000 square meter warehouse in Barra da Tijuca was used to assemble and supply the furniture and fittings for the Olympic Village.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The second warehouse of 90,000 square meters in Duque de Caxias, near the roads that provide access to the venues, contained all the equipment needed for the sporting events.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The medals were produced by the Casa da Moeda do Brasil (the Brazilian National Mint).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The medal design was unveiled on 15 June 2016.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] They were designed to be environmentally friendly using recycled materials; the bronze and silver medals contained 30% recycled materials.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The gold medals were produced using gold that had been mined and extracted according to a set of sustainability criteria, such as being extracted without the use of mercury.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The medals feature a wreath design on the front, and in keeping with tradition, the obverse features Nike, the Greek goddess of victory.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A wooden carrying box accompanied each medal.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Medalists were also awarded a trophy in the shape of the Games' emblem.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In May 2017, an Associated Press article disclosed that over 100 athletes who had won medals at the Rio Olympics reported that their medals were showing some damage, including black spots, flaking, or surface degrading.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Rio officials offered to replace any defective medals and found problems with 6 to 7 percent of all those awarded.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Rio 2016 podiums featured designs and vegetation reminiscent of the city of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The podiums were made from wood and adorned with foliage in keeping with the natural “Look” of the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] They also needed to be light enough to be easily carried and assembled, but also strong enough to support up to 18 athletes on each stand.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The blue, green, yellow and orange colours that feature on the podium were symbolic of the Games' visual identity, inspired by Brazil’s harmonic diversity.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] All materials were organic and celebrated the tropical nature of Brazil, with the intent to be reused as furniture after the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] After the games, the podium from the Brazilian national football team's Olympic gold medal, that was 12 meters wide, was being auctioned off.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] It was divided into five parts, with values ranging from R$ 505,00 to R$ 925,00.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In the end, it was businessman Sérgio Santos who ended up buying the piece.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit on 21 April 2016 at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, the traditional start of the Greek phase of the torch relay.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The flame was handed over to the Brazilian organisers in a ceremony at the Panathenaic Stadium in Athens on 27 April.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A brief stop-off was made in Switzerland to visit the IOC headquarters and the Olympic Museum in Lausanne, as well as the United Nations Office at Geneva.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The torch relay began its journey around Brazil on 3 May at the capital Brasília.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The flame visited more than 300 Brazilian cities, including all 26 state capitals and the Brazilian Federal District.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The relay ended in Rio de Janeiro on 5 August when the flame was used to light the Olympic cauldron during the opening ceremony.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Unpaid volunteers performed a variety of tasks before and during the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A target of 50,000 volunteers was set as early as 2012.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] More than 240,000 applications were received when recruitment took place in 2014.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The clothing worn by the volunteers included yellow polo shirts and jackets, beige trousers, white socks, and green trainers, which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Volunteers also wore photo accreditation badges which were allocated to officials, athletes, family members, and media, allowing them to gain access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Many volunteers gave up their roles due to long working hours and insufficient free meals.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The ticket prices were announced on 16 September 2014, all of which were sold in Brazilian reais (BRL).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A total of 7.5 million tickets were to be sold in total, with ticket prices ranging from BRL 40 for many events to BRL 4,600 for the most expensive seats at the opening ceremony.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] About 3.8 million of these tickets were available for BRL 70 or less.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As an aspect of its bid, Rio's organizing committee planned to focus on sustainability and environmental protection as a theme of the 2016 Games, going on to dub them a "Green Games for a Blue Planet".
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] However, some of these projects met with delays or faced economic shortfalls, leading some critics to believe that Rio would not be able to accomplish them.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The focus on environmental protection also influenced the implementation of certain Olympic protocols.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] To reduce emissions, the Olympic cauldron was designed to be smaller than previous iterations, using a kinetic sculpture to enhance its appearance in place of a larger body of flames.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The bronze and silver medals, as well as the ribbons on all medals, were designed to incorporate recycled materials.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The athletes were not presented with flowers during the medal ceremonies, as had been the tradition at previous Olympics (although floral displays were still used as part of the staging of medal presentations).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The organizers considered the practice to be wasteful because the flowers were often thrown away and "would struggle to survive in the tropical Brazilian climate" if kept.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The podiums were designed using materials that could be recycled to make furniture.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Future Arena, the venue for the handball competitions, was designed as a temporary modular structure whose components could be reconstructed after the Games to build schools.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] However, as of November 2017, the arena was still standing due to lack of funds to dismantle it and no allocation of funds to do so in the 2018 budget.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Portions of the opening ceremony were dedicated to the issue of climate change.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony took place at Maracanã Stadium on 5 August 2016, directed by Fernando Meirelles, Daniela Thomas, and Andrucha Waddington.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The ceremony highlighted aspects of Brazilian history and culture, and featured a segment narrated by Fernanda Montenegro and Judi Dench with an appeal to environmental conservation and the prevention of global warming.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The crowd in the stadium numbered 60,000 and the event was broadcast to an estimated global audience of three billion.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The ceremony included the inaugural presentation of the Olympic Laurel, an honor bestowed by the IOC on those that have made "significant achievements in education, culture, development and peace through sport"; the trophy was awarded to Kenyan athlete Kipchoge Keino.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Games were officially opened by the acting president of Brazil, Michel Temer.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Olympic cauldron was lit by long-distance runner Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima, the men's marathon bronze medalist at the 2004 Olympics, who had also received the IOC's Pierre de Coubertin medal for sportsmanship after being attacked by a spectator and losing his lead in the race.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The cauldron was originally expected to be lit by Brazilian footballer Pelé, but he declined to participate due to health problems.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Following the opening ceremony, a public cauldron was lit in front of the Candelária Church by Jorge Gomes, a 14-year-old Brazilian athlete who had escaped from poverty to train as a runner.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympic program featured 28 sports encompassing 306 medal events.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The number of events in each of 42 discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In April 2008, the IOC began accepting applications for two new sports to be introduced to the Olympic programme.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Baseball and softball (which were both dropped in 2005), karate, squash, golf, roller sports, and rugby union all applied to be included on the programme.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Formal presentations were made to the IOC executive board in June 2009.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In August, the executive board initially gave its approval to rugby sevens—a seven-player version of rugby union—by a majority vote; baseball/softball, roller sports, and squash were removed from contention, leaving golf, karate, and rugby sevens in the running.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A final vote was held on 9 October 2009, the closing day of the 121st IOC Session.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] At this session, a new voting system was in place: a sport now needed only a simple majority from the full IOC committee for approval rather than the two-thirds majority previously required.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The 121st IOC Session decided to add rugby sevens and golf to the Rio 2016 Olympic programme.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The tally for rugby was 81 in favor, with eight against, and golf was approved by 63 votes to 26.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Neither of these two sports was new to the Summer Olympics; rugby last featured in 1924, and golf in 1904.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In May 2012, the International Sailing Federation announced that windsurfing would be replaced by kitesurfing at the 2016 Olympics, but this decision was reversed in November.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Twenty-seven world records and ninety-one Olympic records were set during the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The records were set in archery, athletics, canoeing, cycling track, modern pentathlon, rowing, shooting, swimming, and weightlifting.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] A number of events, most notably in aquatics, beach volleyball and track and field, were scheduled with sessions and matches occurring as late as 10:00 p.m. to midnight BRT.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As Brasília time is only one hour ahead of the U.S.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Eastern Time Zone, certain marquee events were scheduled to occur during U.S. primetime hours (traditionally 8:00 to 11:00 p.m.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] ET, 9:00 p.m. to midnight BRT), allowing them to be broadcast live on the east coast as opposed to being delayed.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] This practice was also beneficial to Globo; a Brazilian critic noted that the network very rarely preempts its primetime telenovelas, as they are among the highest-rated programs in the country.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony of the 2016 Summer Olympics was held on 21 August 2016 from 20:00 to 22:50 BRT at the Maracanã Stadium.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The creative director for the ceremony was Rosa Magalhães.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Amid heavy rainfall, the ceremony began with interpretive dancers representing various landmarks in the host city.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Martinho da Vila then performed a rendition of "Carinhoso" by Pixinguinha.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In another segment, introducing the athletes, singer Roberta Sá channeled Carmen Miranda, the fruit-headdress-wearing, mid-century Hollywood diva who endures as a beloved camp figure.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Parade of Flags followed shortly after a choir of 27 children, representing the states of Brazil, sang the Brazilian national anthem.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Oxford Olympics Study 2016 estimated the out-turn cost of the Rio 2016 Summer Olympics at US$4.6 billion in 2015-dollars.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Indirect capital costs were not included, such as for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, for hotel upgrades, or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Rio Olympics' cost of US$4.6 billion compares with costs of US$40–44 billion for Beijing 2008 and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the two most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The average cost of the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] All 205 National Olympic Committees qualified at least one athlete.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The first three nations to qualify athletes for the Games were Germany, Great Britain, and the Netherlands, who each qualified four athletes for the team dressage by winning medals in the team event at the 2014 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As host nation, Brazil received automatic entry for some sports including in all cycling disciplines and six places for weightlifting events.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympics were the first Games in which Kosovo and South Sudan were eligible to participate.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Bulgarian and Russian weightlifters were banned from Rio Olympics for numerous anti-doping violations.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Kuwait was banned in October 2015 for the second time in five years over government interference in the country's Olympic committee.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Kuwaiti athletes instead participated as "Independent Olympic Athletes".
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Due to the European migrant crisis and other reasons, the IOC allowed athletes to compete as Independent Olympians under the Olympic Flag.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] During the previous Summer Olympic Games, refugees were ineligible to compete because of their inability to represent their home NOCs.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] On 2 March 2016, the IOC finalized plans for a specific Refugee Olympic Team (ROT); out of 43 refugee athletes deemed potentially eligible, 10 were chosen to form the team.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Due to the suspension of the National Olympic Committee of Kuwait, participants from Kuwait were allowed to participate under the Olympic Flag as Independent Olympic Athletes.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In November 2015, Russia was provisionally suspended from all international track and field athletic competitions by the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) following a World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) report into a doping program in the country.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The IAAF announced that it would allow individual Russian athletes to apply for "exceptional eligibility" to participate in the Games as "neutral" athletes if it was independently verified that they had not engaged in doping nor in the Russian doping program.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] On 24 July 2016, the IOC rejected the IAAF and WADA's recommendations to allow athletes to compete neutrally, stating that the Olympic Charter "does not foresee such 'neutral athletes'" and that it was each country's National Olympic Committee decision on which athletes would be competing.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] As a result, Russian athletes competed under the Russian flag, although they would compete under a neutral flag in the 2018 Winter Olympics following several developments concerning the doping investigation.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] During the Games, some countries and continents had a national house.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] These temporary meeting places for supporters, athletes and other followers were located throughout Rio de Janeiro.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] This is currently based on the schedule released on the same day as ticket sales began, 31 March 2015.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The top ten listed NOCs by the number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil finished in 13th place with a total of 19 medals (7 gold, 6 silver, and 6 bronze).
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Olympic Broadcasting Services served as the host broadcaster for the 2016 Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Produced from a total of seven mobile units, OBS distributed 40,000 hours of television footage and 60,000 hours of digital footage of the Games to its international rightsholders.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, digital-oriented footage exceeded the amount of television-oriented footage.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in the Barra da Tijuca cluster.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] NHK and OBS once again filmed portions of the Games, including the opening ceremony and selected events, in 8K resolution video.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Additionally, expanding upon a 180-degree trial at the 2016 Winter Youth Olympics, 85 hours of video content were originated in 360-degree virtual reality formats.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In the United States, NBCUniversal offered 4K content downconverted from the 8K footage and with HDR and Dolby Atmos support, to participating television providers.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Owing to their expertise in domestic broadcasts of the new sports introduced in Rio, NBCU and Sky New Zealand staff handled the production of the golf and rugby sevens events on behalf of OBS.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In August 2009, the IOC reached a deal to sell domestic broadcast rights for the 2016 Summer Olympics to Grupo Globo.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Replacing Record, the deal covers free-to-air coverage on Rede Globo, pay TV, and digital rights to the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In turn, Globo sublicensed partial free-to-air rights to Record, along with Band.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] IOC board member Richard Carrión described the agreement as "unprecedented", touting that "by working with Brazil's leading media organizations, we are confident that this represents a great deal for Olympic fans in the region.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] In November 2017, the International Olympic Committee announced the winners of the Golden rings in six categories for the best broadcast coverage of the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Sports Production was awarded to Beach Volleyball, produced by Geoff Johnson and directed by Greg Breakell and Gary Milkis.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The production for the cycling road race and Sailing came second and third.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The next category was the best Olympic feature, for which TV Globo's show *Esporte Espetacular* finished third, and CCTV China's feature *A Sequel of Love* came second.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The winner was NBC Olympics for their feature *The Most Beautiful Thing*.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The third category was The Best Athlete Profile, for which RTBF from Belgium collected the third place prize for their profile of Nafi Thiam.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Globo went one better than the previous category coming second with their profile of Isaquias Queiroz.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The winner of the category again was NBC, this time for their piece on Wayde van Niekerk.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Best On-Air Promotion was announced next, with the BBC Sport winning with NBC coming second this time and BNT from Bulgaria finishing third.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Digital Service went to NBC, with ZDF and SporTV/Globosat picking up the second and third places.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Programme was awarded to SporTV/Globosat, while TV Globo and BBC Sport completed the podium.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] On 24 November 2014, the official mascots of the 2016 Summer Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled, created by São Paulo-based animation company Birdo.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The Olympic mascot Vinicius, named after musician Vinicius de Moraes, represents Brazilian wildlife and carries design traits of cats, monkeys, and birds.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] According to their fictional backgrounds, the mascots "were both born from the joy of Brazilians after it was announced that Rio would host the Games".
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Brand director Beth Lula stated that the mascots were intended to reflect the diversity of Brazil's culture and people.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The names of the mascots were determined by a public vote whose results were announced on 14 December 2014.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The names, which reference the co-writers of the song "The Girl from Ipanema", won over two other sets of names, tallying 44 percent of 323,327 votes.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] At the Olympic wrestling events, coaches were given plush dolls of Vinicius to throw into the ring when they wished to challenge a referee's call.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The official emblem for the 2016 Summer Olympics was designed by Brazilian agency Tatíl Design and was unveiled on 31 December 2010, winning in a competition against 139 agencies.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The emblem represents three figures joined at their arms and feet, with the overall shape reflecting that of Sugarloaf Mountain.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] It was also designed to have a three-dimensional form, which designer Fred Gelli claimed made it the first 3D logo in the history of the Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] The logo has been noted as evoking Henri Matisse's painting *Dance*.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] There were also allegations by the Colorado-based Telluride Foundation that the logo had been plagiarized from its own; while also consisting of several figures linked in motion, the Telluride Foundation logo contains four figures.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] This was not the first time that the foundation had alleged plagiarism of its logo by a Brazilian event; in 2004, the linked figures element had been copied for the logo of Carnival celebrations in Salvador.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Gelli defended the allegations, stating that the concept of figures linked in embrace was not inherently original, as it was "an ancient reference" and "in the collective unconscious".
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p01] Gelli cited *Dance* as an influence of the logo's concept and stated that the designers had intentionally aimed to make the interpretation of the concept as dissimilar to others as possible.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] However, the Zika virus was not contracted by anyone competing in or attending the Olympics, and the Games went ahead normally with no major incident.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] There is no legally legitimate evidence of impropriety in the choice of Rio to host the Olympic games, at least as far as the Brazilian Olympic Committee or the politicians involved in the process are concerned.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] However, the specialized media raised suspicions about it.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In 2014, Operation Car Wash, an investigation by the Federal Police of Brazil, uncovered unprecedented money laundering and corruption at the state-controlled oil company Petrobras.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In early 2015, a series of protests against alleged corruption by the government of President Dilma Rousseff began in Brazil, triggered by revelations that numerous politicians were involved in the Petrobras affair.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] By early 2016, the scandal had escalated into a full-blown political crisis affecting not only President Rousseff, but also former President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, resulting in widespread demonstrations involving millions of protesters, both anti- and pro-Rousseff.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] At the same time, Brazil faced its worst economic recession since the 1990s, raising questions about whether the country was adequately prepared to host the Olympic Games against a volatile political and economic backdrop.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] On 12 May 2016, President Rousseff was stripped of her powers and duties for 180 days after an impeachment vote in the Federal Senate, with Vice President Michel Temer standing in as acting president during the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] On 5 October 2017, Brazilian Olympic Committee head Carlos Nuzman was arrested amid a money-laundering investigation into a $2 million payment that was allegedly made to secure votes for the bid to bring the Olympics to Rio.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The money was believed to have been paid to former IAAF president Lamine Diack and his son Papa Massata Diack, who was a member of the IOC at the time of the alleged payment, which was three days before the vote in 2009.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] All three were charged with money laundering, along with the former Rio state governor Sérgio Cabral Filho (who was already in prison for money laundering offenses at the time), Brazilian businessman Arthur Soares, and ex-Brazilian Olympic Committee chief Leonardo Gryner.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] All six were charged with running a criminal organization, money laundering, and violating currency laws in their own native countries.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] On 4 July 2019, it was reported that Cabral told a judge that the money paid to Diack was used to buy as many as nine votes.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Rio mayor Eduardo Paes was also accused of corruption and fraud in relation to the construction of a number of venues for the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In 2024, Nuzman's and Cabral's conviction in this legal case was overturned by the Court.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] An outbreak of the mosquito-borne Zika virus in Brazil raised fears regarding its potential impact on athletes and visitors.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] To prevent puddles of stagnant water that allow mosquitoes to breed, organizers announced plans to perform daily inspections of Olympic venues.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Zika virus transmission was also attributed to inefficient sewage treatment in the area, an issue that was also in the process of being addressed for the Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In May 2016, a group of 150 physicians and scientists sent an open letter to the World Health Organization (WHO), calling upon them to, according to co-author Arthur Caplan, have "an open, transparent discussion of the risks of holding the Olympics as planned in Brazil".
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The WHO dismissed the request, stating that "cancelling or changing the location of the 2016 Olympics [would] not significantly alter the international spread of Zika virus", and that there was "no public health justification" for postponing them.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Some athletes did not attend the Games because of the epidemic.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] On 2 September 2016, however, the World Health Organization reported that there were no confirmed cases of Zika among athletes or visitors during the 2016 Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The Guanabara Bay, whose waters were used for sailing and windsurfing competitions, is heavily polluted.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Among the chief causes of the pollution are uncollected trash fed into the bay via polluted rivers and slums along the coast.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Pollution of the Guanabara has been a long-term issue.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] At the Earth Summit in 1992, officials promised they would begin to address the pollution, but previous attempts to do so have been insufficient.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] As an aspect of their bid for the Games, Rio once again committed to making efforts towards cleaning the bay.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] However, some of these proposed initiatives have faced budgetary issues.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Prior to these efforts, only 17% of Rio's sewage was treated; this raw sewage also leaked into the bay.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Although Rio mayor Eduardo Paes stated that the city might not be able to reach its goal of having 80% of sewage treated, at least 60% of sewage was treated by March 2016, with a projected goal of 65% of sewage being treated by the start of the Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Rio's crime problems also received renewed attention after it was awarded the 2016 Games; mayor Paes stated that the city was facing "big issues" in heightening security, but that such concerns and issues were presented to the IOC throughout the bidding process.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The governor of Rio de Janeiro also highlighted the fact that London faced security problems, with a terrorist attack occurring just a day after it was awarded the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The estimate was that 5,000 men of the National Public Security Force and 22,000 military officers (14,800 Army; 5,900 Navy and 1,300 of the Brazilian Air Force), in addition to the fixed quota of Rio January, would act during the Olympic Games.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] On 21 July 2016, two weeks before the scheduled start of the Games, the Brazilian Federal Police broke up an Islamic jihadist terrorist cell named Ansar al-Khilafah Brazil by arresting 12 people.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In December 2014, media attention began growing when German broadcaster ARD reported on state-sponsored doping in Russia, comparing it to doping in East Germany.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In November 2015, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) published a report, and the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) suspended Russia indefinitely from world track and field events.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The United Kingdom Anti-Doping agency later assisted WADA with testing in Russia.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In June 2016, they reported they were unable to fully carry out their work, and noted intimidation by armed Federal Security Service (FSB) agents.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In response to these findings, WADA announced that RUSADA should be regarded as non-compliant with respect to the World Anti-Doping Code, and recommended that Russia be banned from competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] The IOC rejected the recommendation, stating that the IOC and each sport's international federation would make decisions on each athlete's individual basis.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] A day before the opening ceremony, 278 athletes were cleared to compete under the Russian flag, while 111 were removed because of doping.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] In contrast, the entire Kuwaiti team was banned from competing under their own flag for a non-doping related matter.
[src:leeds/2016-rio-olympics-p02] Unlike the IOC, the International Paralympic Committee voted unanimously to ban the entire Russian team from the 2016 Summer Paralympics, and suspended the Russian Paralympic Committee after it found evidence that the DPM was also in operation at the 2014 Winter Paralympics.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds developed as a mill town during the Industrial Revolution alongside other surrounding villages and towns in the West Riding of Yorkshire.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It was also known for its flax industry, iron foundries, engineering and printing, as well as shopping, with several surviving Victorian era arcades, such as Kirkgate Market.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] City status was awarded in 1893, and a populous urban centre formed in the following century which absorbed surrounding villages and overtook the population of nearby York.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The economy of Leeds is the most diverse of all the UK's main employment centres, has seen the fastest rate of private-sector jobs growth of any UK city and has the highest ratio of private to public sector jobs.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is home to over 109,000 companies, generating 5% of England's total economic output, at £60.5 billion, and is also ranked as a high sufficiency city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is considered the cultural, financial and commercial heart of the West Yorkshire Urban Area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is also served by five universities, and has the fourth largest student population in the country and the country's fourth largest urban economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The student population has stimulated growth of the nightlife in the city and there are ample facilities for sporting and cultural activities, including classical and popular music festivals, and a varied collection of museums.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city is home to the Leeds United football club.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has multiple motorway links such as the M1, M62 and A1(M).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city's railway station is, alongside Manchester Piccadilly, the busiest of its kind in Northern England.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Public transport, rail and road networks in the city and wider region are widespread.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It is the county's largest settlement, with a population of 536,280, while the larger City of Leeds district has a population of 812,000 (2021 census).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city is part of the fourth-largest built-up area by population in the United Kingdom, West Yorkshire Built-up Area, with a 2011 census population of 1.7 million.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This name originally referred to the forested area covering most of the Brittonic kingdom of Elmet, which existed during the 5th century into the early 7th century.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Bede states in the fourteenth chapter of his *Ecclesiastical History*, in a discussion of an altar surviving from a church erected by Edwin of Northumbria, that it is located in *...regione quae vocatur Loidis* (Latin, "the region which is called Loidis").
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] An inhabitant of Leeds is locally known as a *Loiner*, a word of uncertain origin.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The term *Leodensian* is also used, from the city's Latin name.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds developed as a market town in the Middle Ages, as part of the local agricultural economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Before the Industrial Revolution, it became a co-ordination centre for the manufacture of woollen cloth, and white broadcloth was traded at its White Cloth Hall.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds handled one-sixth of England's export trade in 1770.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Growth, initially in textiles, was accelerated by the creation of the Aire and Calder Navigation in 1699 (with major additional works in the 18th century), and the Leeds and Liverpool Canal in 1816.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the late Georgian era, William Lupton was one of a number of central Leeds landowners, some of whom, like him, were also textile manufacturers.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] At the time of his death in 1828, Lupton occupied the enclosed fields of the manor of Leeds, his estate including a mill, reservoir, substantial house and outbuildings.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Mechanical engineering, initially supplying tools and machinery for the textile sector, rapidly became a diverse industry.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Alongside technological advances and industrial expansion, Leeds retained an interest in trading in agricultural commodities, with the Corn Exchange opening in 1864.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Marshall's Mill was one of the first of many factories constructed in Leeds from around 1790 when the most significant were woollen finishing and flax mills.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Manufacturing diversified by 1914 to printing, engineering, chemicals and clothing manufacture.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Decline in manufacturing during the 1930s was temporarily reversed by a switch to producing military uniforms and munitions during the Second World War.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] However, by the 1970s, the clothing industry was in irreversible decline, facing cheap foreign competition.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The contemporary economy has been shaped by Leeds City Council's vision of building a '24-hour European city' and 'capital of the north'.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city has developed from the decay of the post-industrial era to become a telephone banking centre, connected to the electronic infrastructure of the modern global economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There has been growth in the corporate and legal sectors, and increased local affluence has led to an expanding retail sector, including the luxury goods market.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds City Region Enterprise Zone was launched in April 2012 to promote development in four sites along the A63 East Leeds Link Road.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds was a manor and township in the large ancient parish of *Leeds St Peter*, in the Skyrack wapentake of the West Riding of Yorkshire.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Borough of Leeds was created in 1207, when Maurice Paynel, lord of the manor, granted a charter to a small area of the manor, close to the river crossing, in what is now the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] King James I granted the borough to his wife, Anne of Denmark, and in 1612, she ordered a survey of the borough; in 1615 she was petitioned to remove the strict Calvinist preacher Alexander Cooke as vicar of Leeds, but she refused.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The inhabitants petitioned Charles I for a charter of incorporation, which was granted in 1626.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The new charter incorporated the entire parish, including all eleven townships, as the Borough of Leeds and withdrew the earlier charter.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Improvement commissioners were set up in 1755 for paving, lighting, and cleansing of the main streets, including Briggate and further powers were added in 1790 to improve the water supply.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The borough corporation was reformed under the provisions of Municipal Corporations Act 1835.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds Borough Police force was formed in 1836, and Leeds Town Hall was completed by the corporation in 1858.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 1866, Leeds and each of the other townships in the borough became civil parishes.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The borough became a county borough in 1889, giving it independence from the newly formed West Riding County Council and it gained city status in 1893.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 1904 the Leeds parish absorbed Beeston, Chapel Allerton, Farnley, Headingley cum Burley and Potternewton from within the borough.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the twentieth century the county borough initiated a series of significant territorial expansions, growing from 21,593 acres (87.38 km2) in 1911 to 40,612 acres (164.35 km2) in 1961.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 1912 the parish and county borough of Leeds absorbed Leeds Rural District, consisting of the parishes of Roundhay and Seacroft; and Shadwell, which had been part of Wetherby Rural District.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] On 1 April 1925, the parish of Leeds was expanded to cover the whole borough.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The county borough was abolished on 1 April 1974, and its former area was combined with that of the municipal boroughs of Morley and Pudsey; the urban districts of Aireborough, Horsforth, Otley, Garforth and Rothwell; and parts of the rural districts of Tadcaster, Wetherby, and Wharfedale.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This area formed a metropolitan district in the county of West Yorkshire.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It gained both borough and city status and is known as the City of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Initially, local government services were provided by Leeds City Council and West Yorkshire County Council.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] When the county council was abolished in 1986, the city council absorbed its functions, and some powers passed to organisations such as the West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Authority.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] From 1988 two run-down and derelict areas close to the city centre were designated for regeneration and became the responsibility of Leeds Development Corporation, outside the planning remit of the city council.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Planning powers were restored to the local authority in 1995 when the development corporation was wound up.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds City Council are working with partners across the city to celebrate the four hundredth anniversary of its Royal Charter in 2026.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 1801, 42% of the population of Leeds lived outside the township, in the wider borough.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Cholera outbreaks in 1832 and 1849 caused the authorities to address the problems of drainage, sanitation, and water supply.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Water was pumped from the River Wharfe, but by 1860 it was too heavily polluted to be usable.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Following the Leeds Waterworks Act 1867 (30 & 31 Vict. c. cxli) three reservoirs were built at Lindley Wood, Swinsty, and Fewston in the Washburn Valley north of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Residential growth occurred in Holbeck and Hunslet from 1801 to 1851, but, as these townships became industrialised new areas were favoured for middle class housing.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Land south of the river was developed primarily for industry and secondarily for back-to-back workers' dwellings.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Leeds Improvement Act 1866 (29 & 30 Vict. c. clvii) sought to improve the quality of working class housing by restricting the number of homes that could be built in a single terrace.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Holbeck and Leeds formed a continuous built-up area by 1858, with Hunslet nearly meeting them.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the latter half of the nineteenth century, population growth in Hunslet, Armley, and Wortley outstripped that of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] When pollution became a problem, the wealthier residents left the industrial conurbation to live in Headingley, Potternewton and Chapel Allerton which led to a 50% increase in the population of Headingley and Burley from 1851 to 1861.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The middle-class flight from the industrial areas led to development beyond the borough at Roundhay and Adel.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The introduction of the electric tramway led to intensification of development in Headingley and Potternewton and expansion outside the borough into Roundhay.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Two private gas supply companies were taken over by the corporation in 1870, and the municipal supply provided street lighting and cheaper gas to homes.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] From the early 1880s, the Yorkshire House-to-House Electricity Company supplied electricity to Leeds until it was purchased by Leeds Corporation and became a municipal supply.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Slum clearance and rebuilding began in Leeds during the interwar period when over 18,000 houses were built by the council on 24 estates in Cross Gates, Middleton, Gipton, Belle Isle and Halton Moor.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The slums of Quarry Hill were replaced by the innovative Quarry Hill flats, which were demolished in 1975.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Another 36,000 houses were built by private sector builders, creating suburbs in Gledhow, Moortown, Alwoodley, Roundhay, Colton, Whitkirk, Oakwood, Weetwood, and Adel.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] After 1949 a further 30,000 sub-standard houses were demolished by the council and replaced by 151 medium-rise and high-rise blocks of council flats in estates at Seacroft, Armley Heights, Tinshill, and Brackenwood.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has seen great expenditure on regenerating the city, attracting in investments and flagship projects, as found in Leeds city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Many developments boasting luxurious penthouse apartments have been built close to the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city centre lies at about 206 feet (63 m) above sea level while the district ranges from 1,115 feet (340 m) in the far west on the slopes of Ilkley Moor to about 33 feet (10 m) where the rivers Aire and Wharfe cross the eastern boundary.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The centre of Leeds is part of a continuously built-up area extending to Pudsey, Bramley, Horsforth, Alwoodley, Seacroft, Middleton and Morley.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has the second highest population of any local authority district in the UK (after Birmingham), and the second greatest area of any English metropolitan district (after Doncaster), extending 15 miles (24 km) from east to west, and 13 miles (21 km) from north to south.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The northern boundary follows the River Wharfe for several miles but crosses the river to include the part of Otley which lies north of the river.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Over 60% of the Leeds district is green belt land and the city centre is less than twenty miles (32 km) from the Yorkshire Dales National Park, which has some of the most spectacular scenery and countryside in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Inner and southern areas of Leeds lie on a layer of coal measure sandstones.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] To the north parts are built on older sandstone and gritstones and to the east it extends into the magnesian limestone belt.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The land use in the central areas of Leeds is overwhelmingly urban.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Attempts to define the exact geographic meaning of Leeds lead to a variety of concepts of its extent, varying by context include the area of the city centre, the urban sprawl, the administrative boundaries, and the functional region.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has a varying extent by context such as the city centre, the built-up sprawl around the centre, administrative boundaries and the travel to work area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city centre lies in a narrow section of the Aire Valley at about 206 feet (63 m) above sea level.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The land use in the central areas of Leeds is overwhelmingly urban. while being less than twenty miles (32 km) from the rural Yorkshire Dales National Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It is contained within the Leeds Inner Ring Road, formed from parts of the A58 road, A61 road, A64 road, A643 road and the M621 motorway.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Briggate, the principal north–south shopping street, is pedestrianised and Queen Victoria Street, a part of the Victoria Quarter, is enclosed under a glass roof.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Millennium Square is a significant urban focal point.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Inner and southern areas of Leeds lie on a layer of coal measure sandstones forming the Yorkshire Coalfield.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Outside Leeds centre, there are a number of suburbs and exurbs within the district.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Some of Leeds suburbs include Headingley, Harehills and Hunslet, while exurbs include Pudsey, Horsforth and Morley.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Lying in the eastern foothills of the Pennines, there is a significant variation in elevation within the city's built-up area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The district ranges from 1,115 feet (340 m) in the far west on the slopes of Ilkley Moor to about 33 feet (10 m) where the rivers Aire and Wharfe cross the eastern boundary.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Land rises to 198 m (650 ft) in Cookridge, just 6 miles (9.7 km) from the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The northern boundary follows the River Wharfe for several miles (several kilometres), but it crosses the river to include the part of Otley which lies north of the river.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Leeds postcode area covers most of the City of Leeds district and is almost entirely made up of the Leeds post town.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Otley, Wetherby, Tadcaster, Pudsey and Ilkley are separate post towns within the postcode area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This is achieved by restricting inappropriate development within the designated areas, and imposing stricter conditions on permitted building.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Over 60% of the Leeds district is green belt land and it surrounds the settlement, preventing further sprawl towards nearby communities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Larger outlying towns and villages are exempt from the green belt area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] However, smaller villages, hamlets and rural areas are 'washed over' by the designation.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The green belt was first adopted in 1960, and the size in the borough in 2017 amounted to some 33,970 hectares (339.7 km2; 131.2 sq mi).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has a climate that is oceanic (Köppen: *Cfb*), and influenced by the Pennines.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Summers are usually mild, with moderate rainfall, while winters are chilly, cloudy with occasional snow and frost.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The nearest official weather recording station is at Bingley, some twelve miles (20 km) away at a higher altitude.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] July and August are the warmest months, with a mean temperature of 15 °C (59 °F), while the coldest months are January and February, with a mean temperature of 3 °C (37 °F).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Temperatures above 30 °C (86 °F) and below −10 °C (14 °F) are not very common but can happen occasionally.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Temperatures at Leeds Bradford Airport fell to −12.6 °C (9.3 °F) in December 2010 and reached 31.8 °C (89 °F) at Leeds city centre in August 2003.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The record temperature for Leeds is 39.8 °C (104 °F) recorded on 19 July 2022 at Bramham 10 miles east of Leeds City Centre; it is likely that the temperature within Leeds City Centre exceeded this but the Leeds weather centre closed in 2000.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] As is typical for many sprawling cities in areas of varying topography, temperatures can change depending on location.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Average July and August daytime highs exceed 22 °C (72 °F) (a value comparable to South East England) in a small area just to the south east of the city centre, where the elevation declines to under 20 metres (66 feet).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This is 2 °C (3.6 °F) milder than the typical summer temperature at Leeds Bradford airport weather station (shown in the chart below), at an elevation of 208 metres (682 feet).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Situated on the eastern side of the Pennines, Leeds is among the driest cities in the United Kingdom, with an annual rainfall of 660 mm (25.98 in).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Though extreme weather in Leeds is relatively rare, thunderstorms, blizzards, gale-force winds and even tornadoes have struck the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The last reported tornado occurred on 14 September 2006, causing trees to uproot and signal failures at Leeds City railway station.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds forms the main area of the City of Leeds metropolitan borough of West Yorkshire.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This district includes Leeds itself as well as surrounding towns of Horsforth, Morley, Otley, Pudsey, Rothwell and Wetherby, Leeds is the central city of the Leeds City Region, a classification for the city region's metropolitan area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city region has a population of over 3 million, making it the second most populated metropolitan city region in the United Kingdom, behind Greater London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In January 2011, Leeds was named as one of five "cities to watch" in a report published by Centre for Cities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The report shows that the average resident in Leeds earns £471 per week, 17th nationally and 30.9% of Leeds residents had NVQ4+ high-level qualifications, 15th nationally.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Employment in Leeds was 68.8% in the period June 2012 to June 2013, which was lower than the national average, whilst unemployment was higher than the national average at 9.6% over the same time period.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is overall less deprived than other large UK cities and average income is above regional averages.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] At the time of the United Kingdom Census 2001, the Leeds urban subdivision occupied an area of 109 square kilometres (42 sq mi) and had a population of 443,247; making it the fourth-most populous urban subdivision within England and the fifth largest within the United Kingdom.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The population density was 4,066 inhabitants per square kilometre (10,530/sq mi), slightly higher than the rest of the West Yorkshire Urban Area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It accounts for 20% of the area and 62% of the population of the City of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The population of the urban subdivision had a 100 to 93.1 female–male ratio.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Of those over 16 years old, 39.4% were single (never married) and 35.4% married for the first time.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The urban subdivision's 188,890 households included 35% one-person, 27.9% married couples living together, 8.8% were co-habiting couples, and 5.7% single parents with their children.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is the largest component of the West Yorkshire Urban Area and is counted by Eurostat as part of the Leeds-Bradford larger urban zone.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Leeds travel to work area in 2001 included all of the City of Leeds, a northern strip of the City of Bradford, the eastern part of Kirklees, and a section of southern North Yorkshire; it occupies 751 square kilometres (290 sq mi).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2011, the Leeds urban subdivision had a population of 474,632 and had an area of 112 square kilometres (43 sq mi) with a population density of 4,238 inhabitants per square kilometre (10,980/sq mi).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It is bounded by, and physically attached to, the other towns of Garforth to the east, Morley to the southwest and Pudsey to the west, all being within the wider borough.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] 63% of the borough's population of 751,485 live in the urban subdivision, while it takes up only 21% of its total area of 552 km2.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] At the time of the 2021 UK Census, the district had a total population of 811,953, representing a 8% growth since the previous census ten years earlier.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] According to the 2001 UK Census, there were 301,614 households in Leeds; 33.3% were married couples living together, 31.6% were single-person households, 9.0% were co-habiting couples and 9.8% were single parents, following a similar trend to the rest of England.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The population density was 1,967/km2 (5,090/sq mi) and for every 100 females, there were 93.5 males.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is a diverse city with over 75 ethnic groups, and with ethnic minorities representing 21% of the total population.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has seen many new different countries of birth as of the UK Census including Pakistan, Zimbabwe, Iran, India and Nigeria all included in the top ten countries of birth in the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Large Pakistani communities can be seen in wards such as Gipton and Harehills.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Chapel Allerton is known for having a large Caribbean community.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The majority of people in Leeds identify themselves as Christian.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The proportion of Muslims (3.0% of the population) is average for the country.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has the third-largest community of Jews in the United Kingdom, after those of London and Manchester.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The areas of Alwoodley and Moortown contain sizeable Jewish communities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] 16.8% of Leeds residents in the 2001 census declared themselves as having "No Religion", which is broadly in line with the figure for the whole of the UK (also 8.1% "religion not stated").
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The crime rate in Leeds is well above the national average, like many other English major cities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In July 2006, the think tank Reform calculated rates of crime for different offences and has related this to populations of major urban areas (defined as towns over 100,000 population).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds was 11th in this rating (excluding London boroughs, 23rd including London boroughs).
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The City of Leeds is the local government district covering Leeds, and the local authority is Leeds City Council.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The council is composed of 99 councillors, three for each of the district's wards.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Elections are held three years out of four, on the first Thursday of May.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] One third of the councillors are elected, for a four-year term, in each election.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The council is currently controlled by Labour.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds City Council is the primary provider of local government services for the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The district is in the Yorkshire and the Humber region of England.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In March 2020, along with the four other Local Authorities in West Yorkshire, Leeds City Council agreed a Devolution Deal with the UK Government.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This resulted in the election of a Metro Mayor for West Yorkshire in 2021.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The mayor leads the West Yorkshire Combined Authority which was first established in 2014, and is based in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Most of the district is an unparished area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the unparished area, there is no lower tier of government.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Outside the unparished area, there are 31 civil parishes, represented by parish councils.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] These are the lowest tier of local government and absorb some limited functions from Leeds City Council in their areas.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has the most diverse economy of all the UK's main employment centres.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It has seen the fastest rate of private sector jobs growth of any UK city and has the highest ratio of public to private sector jobs of all the UK's Core Cities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city had the third-largest jobs total by local authority area with 480,000 in employment and self-employment at the beginning of 2015.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] 24.7% were in public administration, education and health, 23.9% were in banking, finance and insurance and 21.4% were in distribution, hotels and restaurants.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It is in the banking, finance and insurance sectors that Leeds differs most from the financial structure of the region and the nation.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There are 130,100 jobs in the city centre, accounting for 31% of all jobs in the wider district.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2007, 47,500 jobs were in finance and business, 42,300 in public services, and 19,500 in retail and distribution.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] 43% of finance sector jobs in the district are contained in Leeds city centre and 44% of those employed in the city centre live more than nine kilometres (5.6 miles) away.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2011, the financial and services industry in Leeds was worth £2.1 billion, the fifth-largest in the UK, behind London, Edinburgh, Manchester and Birmingham.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Tertiary industries such as retail, call centres, offices and media have contributed to a high rate of economic growth.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city also hosts the only subsidiary office of the Bank of England in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2012 GVA for the city was recorded at £18.8 billion, with the entire Leeds City Region generating a £56 billion economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Key sectors include finance, retail, leisure and the visitor economy, construction, manufacturing and the creative and digital industries.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It has one of the most diverse economies of all the UK's main employment centres and has seen the fastest rate of private-sector jobs growth of any UK city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It also has the highest ratio of private to public sector jobs of all the UK's Core Cities, with 77% of its workforce working in the private sector.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has the third-largest jobs total by local authority area, with 480,000 in employment and self-employment at the beginning of 2015.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is ranked as a "High Sufficiency" level city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Today, Leeds has become the largest legal and financial centre outside London, with the financial and insurance services industry worth £13 billion to the city's economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Office developments, also traditionally located in the inner area, have expanded south of the River Aire and total 11,000,000 square feet (1,000,000 m2) of space.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the period from 1999 to 2008 £2.5 billion of property development was undertaken in central Leeds; of which £711 million has been offices, £265 million retail, £389 million leisure and £794 million housing.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city saw several firsts, including the oldest-surviving film in existence, *Roundhay Garden Scene* (1888), and the 1767 invention of soda water.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Major companies based in the city include William Hill, Channel 4, International Personal Finance, Asda, Leeds Building Society and Northern Foods.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Capita Group, KPMG, Direct Line, Aviva, Yorkshire Building Society, BT Group, Telefónica Europe (O2 Ltd) and TD Waterhouse all also have a considerable presence in the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In addition to other national governmental offices, the city is home to a large Department for Work and Pensions office building located in Quarry Hill, notable for its imposing design.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is the UK's third-largest manufacturing centre and 50% of the UK's manufacturing base is within a two-hour drive of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] With around 1,800 firms and 39,000 employees, Leeds manufacturing firms account for 8.8% of total employment in the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The largest sub-sectors are engineering, printing and publishing, food and drink, chemicals and medical technology.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Manufacturing and distribution accounted for £26 million of new property development in the period.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There is an established creative industry in the city, particularly in the digital gaming sector.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] A number of large developers have studios in and around the city, including Activision, developers of the mobile versions of the *Call of Duty* series, and Rockstar Leeds, developers of the *Grand Theft Auto* series.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2009 Leeds was the first city outside London to host the Eurogamer Expo.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is the largest centre outside London for financial and business services.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Over the next ten years, the economy is forecast to grow by 25% with financial and business services set to generate over half of GVA growth over that period with Finance and business services accounting for 38% of total output.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The finance and business service sector account for 38% of total output with more than 30 national and international banks located in the city, including an office of the Bank of England.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has over 30 national and international banks, many of whose northern or regional offices are based in the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] It is the headquarters for First Direct and Yorkshire Bank, and has large Barclays, HSBC, Lloyds Banking Group, NatWest Group and Santander operations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city is also an important centre for equity, venture, infrastructure and risk finance.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The venture capital provider, YFM Equity Partners, founded in Leeds, is now the UK's largest provider of risk capital to small and medium-sized enterprises.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The National Wealth Fund, founded to support economic growth across the United Kingdom, is also based in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There are around 150 law firms operating in Leeds, employing over 6,700 people.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The establishment of an Administrative Court in Leeds in April 2009 reinforced the position of Leeds as one of the UK's key legal centres.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The court previously sat only in London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Tourism is important to the Leeds economy, in 2009 Leeds was the eighth-most visited city in England by UK visitors. and the 13th-most visited city by overseas visitors.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Research by VisitEngland reported that the day visitor market to Leeds attracts 24.9 million people each year, worth over £654 million to the local economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the 2017 Condé Nast Traveler survey of readers, Leeds rated 6th among the 15 best cities in the UK for visitors.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In 2016, Leeds received 27.29 million leisure tourist visits generating over £1.6 billion for the city, according to data from a STEAM survey.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] That was a 15.9% increase in revenue over 2015.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] A 9.7% increase in visits had been recorded since 2013.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The industry supported over 19,000 full-time equivalent jobs in 2016.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In Leeds, 108,000 people work in the public sector—24% of the workforce.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The largest employers are Leeds City Council, with 33,000 staff, and the Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, with 14,000 staff.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds has become a hub of public-sector health bodies.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Department of Health and Social Care (DHSC), NHS England, the Care Quality Commission, NHS Digital, and Public Health England all have large offices in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Europe's largest teaching hospital is also based in Leeds, and is home to the Yorkshire Cancer Centre, the largest of its kind in Europe.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Key government departments and organisations in Leeds include the Department for Work and Pensions, with over 3,000 staff, the DHSC, with over 800 staff, HM Revenue and Customs with over 1,200 staff and the British Library with 1,100 staff.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city centre has a large pedestrian zone.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Briggate is the main shopping street where one can find many well-known British High Street stores, including Marks & Spencer, Costa Coffee, and Harvey Nichols.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Many companies have several stores within Central Leeds and the wider city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds is home to one of the largest indoor markets in Europe, Leeds Kirkgate Market.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The district also has various regular local markets in Otley, Pudsey, and Yeadon.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Between 1987 – 1995, Leeds Kirkgate market was renovated.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The changes have maximised the retail provision in the market without compromising the historical features of the building, so much so that the renovated Kirkgate Market Hall structure was promoted from Grade II to Grade I listing status, and was subsequently nominated for a Civic Trust Award.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There is an annual German Christmas Market ("Christkindelmarkt") based in Millennium Square, usually running from early November to mid-late December.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The 2020 Christmas Market was cancelled because of the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The extensive retail area of Leeds is the principal regional shopping centre for the whole of the Yorkshire and the Humber region, offering a spend of £1.93 billion annually in 2013.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] There are a number of indoor shopping centres in the centre of the city, including the Merrion Centre, St John's Centre, The Core, the Victoria Quarter, The Light, the Corn Exchange, Trinity Leeds, and Victoria Gate.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In total, there are well over 1,000 retail stores, with a combined floorspace of 3,660,000 square feet (340,000 m2) in Leeds City Centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Victoria Quarter is notable for its high-end luxury retailers and impressive architecture.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] 70 stores such as Louis Vuitton, Vivienne Westwood, Diesel, and anchor Harvey Nichols are contained within two iron-wrought Victorian arcades, and a new arcade formed by arcading Queen Victoria Street with the largest expanse of stained glass in Britain.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] In the Churwell area of Leeds is the White Rose Shopping Centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Opening in 1997, the centre has over 100 high street stores anchored by Marks & Spencer, Primark, NEXT, and Sainsbury's.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] On 21 March 2013, a large shopping and leisure complex called Trinity Leeds opened in the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The modern and interactive retail space covers the old Burton Arcades and the former Leeds Shopping Plaza with its main entrance from Briggate.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] On 20 October 2016, Victoria Gate shopping centre opened with its flagship store, John Lewis.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Three quarters of the stores in Victoria Gate were the first for the retailers outside of London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Of the 40,000 people who work in retailing in Leeds, three quarters work in the wider district.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The Springs, located to the east of the city suburbs, just off junction 46 of the M1.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Leeds displays a variety of natural and built landmarks.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Natural landmarks include such diverse sites as the gritstone outcrop of Otley Chevin and the Fairburn Ings RSPB reserve.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The city's parks at Roundhay and Temple Newsam have long been owned and maintained by the council for the benefit of ratepayers and among the open spaces in the centre of Leeds are Millennium Square, City Square, Park Square, and Victoria Gardens.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] This last is the site of the central city war memorial: there are 42 other war memorials in the suburbs, towns and villages in the district.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The built environment embraces edifices of civic pride like Morley Town Hall and the trio of buildings in Leeds, Leeds Town Hall, Corn Exchange, and Leeds City Museum, by the architect Cuthbert Brodrick.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] The two white buildings on the Leeds skyline are the Parkinson building of Leeds University and the Civic Hall, with golden owls adorning the tops of the latter's twin spires.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Armley Mills, Tower Works, with its campanile-inspired towers, and the Egyptian-style Temple Works hark back to the city's industrial past, while the site and ruins of Kirkstall Abbey display the beauty and grandeur of Cistercian architecture.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Notable churches are Leeds Minster (formerly Leeds Parish Church), St George's Church and Leeds Cathedral, in the city centre, and the Church of St John the Baptist, Adel and Bardsey Parish Church in quieter locations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Notable non-conformist chapels include the Salem Chapel, dating back to 1791 and notably the birthplace of Leeds United Football Club in 1919.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Among other Skyscrapers the 37-storey Sky Plaza to the north of the city centre stands on higher ground so that its 106 metres (348 ft) is higher than Bridgewater Place and the aforementioned, 38-storey Altus House in Arena Quarter, standing at 380 metres.
[src:leeds/leeds-p01] Elland Road (football) and Headingley Stadium (cricket and rugby) are well known to sports enthusiasts, and the White Rose Centre is a well-known retail outlet.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has extensive road, bus and rail networks.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Public transport in the Leeds area is coordinated and developed by West Yorkshire Metro.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city has good rail and road links to the rest of the country.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds railway station is one of the busiest in Britain, and Leeds is connected to the national road network via the A1(M) motorway, M1 motorway and M62 motorway.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city is served by Leeds Bradford Airport.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Plans to improve the public transport network in Leeds have been suggested.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In the 1940s plans to build an extensive underground system were not proceeded with because of the Second World War.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds Supertram in the 1990s at a cost of £500 million was cancelled by the Transport Minister Alistair Darling in 2005 after £40 million had been spent on the project due to unforeseen added costs.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A proposed £250 million re-introduction of trolleybus in 2007; the plans were cancelled in May 2016 citing little value for money, after millions of pounds spent on inquiries.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In June 2019, in his bid to become Prime Minister, Boris Johnson stated that it was "madness" that Leeds did not have a metro system.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In December 2019, in his first Queen's Speech, Johnson promised to "remedy the scandal that Leeds is the largest city in Western Europe without light rail or a metro".
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Plans are in place to improve public transport in Leeds, with upgrades to railway, bus services, and cycle lanes.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A tram system for the city and wider region was announced in 2023.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is the starting point of the A62, A63, A64, A65, A647, and A660 roads.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city is on the A58, A61 roads, the M1 and M62 motorways intersect to the south of Leeds and the A1(M) passes to the east.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The radial M621 takes traffic into central Leeds from the M62 and M1, the Leeds Inner Ring Road has part motorway status and the city has an outer ring road.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Part of the city centre is pedestrianised and encircled by the clockwise-only loop road.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The East Leeds Orbital Route's construction started in summer 2019 and was completed in 2021.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Air quality in Leeds was declared "unsafe" by the World Health Organization in May 2019.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Neville Street, near Leeds railway station, has been measured as the most polluted street outside London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A Clean Air Zone, throughout north Leeds and the city centre, was proposed in 2018.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The plan, similar to the London Low Emission Zone, would charge a daily fee for driving "older models of buses, taxis and HGVs" in the zone.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The zone was planned to start charging vehicles in January 2020, before being cancelled in October 2020 because of improvements in the city's air quality.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds City bus station (on Dyer Street) has long-distance bus services to nearby towns and cities and a small number of local area services.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The main providers are First Leeds and Arriva Yorkshire, the latter serves routes in the city's south.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Harrogate Bus Company provides a service to Harrogate and Ripon.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Keighley Bus Company provides a service to Shipley, Bingley, and Keighley.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Yorkshire Coastliner service runs from Leeds to Scarborough and Whitby via York and Malton.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Also Transdev operates Flyer services to Leeds Bradford Airport.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In March 2024, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority announced that buses in Leeds are set to be operated under public ownership.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] An electric bicycle rental scheme, Leeds City Bikes, operated by Beryl, opened in September 2023.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The bikes are collected from bays around the city centre, and hirers are penalised if they do not return the bike to one of the bays.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2017 Leeds had the third busiest railway station in the UK outside of London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] From the station at New Station Street, West Yorkshire Metro trains operated by Northern run to the suburbs of Leeds, the wider area, national and international connections.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The station has 18 platforms, the most outside of London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The City of Leeds local government area has 16 railway stations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A parkway station serving Leeds Bradford Airport and two other new stations in the area, planned for within the next 20 years, were announced in 2016.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Bradford Airport is in Yeadon, about 8 miles (13 km) to the north-west of the city centre, and has direct flights to eight UK and 70 international destinations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is the tenth busiest airport outside London, with scheduled services to Amsterdam, Dublin, and Barcelona.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There is a direct rail service from Leeds city centre to Manchester Airport.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is claimed by the city council to be one of the best cities in the UK for walking.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds Country Way is a waymarked circular walk of 62 miles (100 km) through the rural outskirts of the city, never more than 7 miles (11 km) from City Square.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Meanwood Valley Trail leads from Woodhouse Moor along Meanwood Beck to Golden Acre Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds extension of the Dales Way follows the Meanwood Valley Trail before it branches off to head towards Ilkley and Windermere.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is on the northern section of the Trans Pennine Trail for walkers and cyclists, and the towpath of the Leeds and Liverpool Canal is another walking and cycling route.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The White Rose Way walking trail to Scarborough begins at City Square.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are many parks and public footpaths in both the urban and rural parts of Leeds, and The Ramblers' Association, YHA and other walking organisations offer sociable walks.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Ramblers' Association publish booklets of walks in and around Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has 16 museums and galleries including nine that are council-run.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Smaller museums in Leeds include Otley Museum; Horsforth Village Museum; ULITA, an Archive of International Textiles; and the museum at Fulneck Moravian Settlement.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds City Museum opened in 2008 at Millennium Square.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is a major museum for the city, showcasing its designated collections of local history; world cultures; natural history; archaeology and fine and decorative arts plus a diverse programme of special exhibitions.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Abbey House Museum is housed in the former gatehouse of Kirkstall Abbey, and includes walk-through Victorian streets and galleries describing the history of the abbey, childhood, and Victorian Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Armley Mills Industrial Museum is housed in what was once the world's largest woollen mill, and includes industrial machinery and railway locomotives.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] This museum also shows the first known moving pictures in the world which were taken in the city, by Louis Le Prince, of a *Roundhay Garden Scene* and of *Leeds Bridge* in 1888.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Thackray Museum of Medicine is a museum of the history of medicine, featuring topics such as Victorian public health, pre-anaesthesia surgery, and safety in childbirth.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is housed in a former workhouse next to St James's Hospital.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The museum closed temporarily in 2019 for a £4 million refurbishment.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The redeveloped museum has since been shortlisted for Art Fund's Museum of the Year award 2021 and received a special commendation from the European Museum Forum in 2023.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Royal Armouries Museum, the United Kingdom's national collection of arms and armour, opened in 1996 in a dramatic modern building when this part of the collection was transferred from the Tower of London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is located a short distance from the city centre at Leeds Dock.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is also one of the largest collections of arms and armour in the world, comprising the UK's National Collection of Arms and Armour, National Artillery Collection, and National Firearms Collection.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Thwaite Mills Watermill Museum is a fully restored 1820s water-powered mill on the River Aire to the east of the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Nearby is the Leeds Museum Discovery Centre (formerly housed at the Leeds Museum Resource Centre in Yeadon), the major storage of items not currently on display in museums, and open to the public by appointment.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city is served by five universities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It has the UK's fourth-largest student population and the country's fourth-largest urban economy.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The University of Leeds has about 31,000 students, of which 21,500 are full-time or sandwich undergraduate degree students, Leeds Beckett University has 25,805 students of which 12,000 are full-time or sandwich undergraduate degree students and 2,100 full-time or sandwich HND students.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Trinity University has just under 3,000 students.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city was voted the best UK university destination by a survey in *The Independent* newspaper.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Further education in Leeds is provided by Elliott Hudson College, Leeds City College (formed by a merger in 2009 and having over 60,000 students), Leeds College of Building, University Technical College (UTC) Leeds, Notre Dame Catholic Sixth Form College, and Leeds Mathematics School.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2018, Leeds embarked on a five-year cultural investment programme, culminating in a year of cultural celebration in 2023.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2023, the city hosted Leeds 2023, an international cultural festival.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Art Gallery, which opened in 1888, houses the best twentieth century collection outside London and a colourful wall painting for the Victorian staircase by Lothar Götz.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The gallery is owned and operated by Leeds City Council and is free to members of the public.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Just next door, The Henry Moore Institute hosts a year-round programme of historical, modern and contemporary exhibitions presenting sculpture from across the world.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Located in the art deco headquarters of the former brewery, The Tetley was a centre for contemporary art; it closed in 2023.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Gallery at 164 is an independent art gallery exhibiting artists, illustrators, photographers and designers working in all types of media.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Stanley & Audrey Burton Gallery offers art exhibitions from the University Art Collection and Treasures of the Brotherton Gallery.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Art is taught in Leeds at Leeds College of Art which has alumni including Henry Moore and Damien Hirst.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds city centre has a variety of statues and sculptures on public display.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city also features an ever-growing host of street art and urban murals, including the UK's tallest mural 'Athena Rising'.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] This mural is part of a city-wide project 'A City Less Grey', initiated by East Street Arts, which won a national award at the Planning Awards 2018.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city has a number of public artworks ranging from traditional statues to contemporary work.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] These include several works by Alfred Drury and one of Joseph Beuys 7000 Oaks.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Two bronze statues stand at Elland Road Stadium celebrating former manager Don Revie and team captain Billy Bremner.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds West Indian Carnival is Western Europe's oldest West Indian Carnival, and the UK's third-largest after the Notting Hill and Nottingham Carnival.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It attracts around 100,000 people over 2 days to the streets of Chapeltown and Harehills.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There is a large procession that finishes at Potternewton Park, where there are stalls, entertainment and refreshments.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds Festival, featuring some of the biggest names in rock and indie music, takes place every year in Bramham Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds Asian Festival, formerly the Leeds Mela, is held in Roundhay Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Otley Folk Festival (patron: Nic Jones), Walking Festival, Carnival, and Victorian Christmas Fayre are annual events.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Light Night Leeds takes place each October, and many venues in the city are open to the public for Heritage Open Days in September.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds International Pianoforte Competition, established in 1963 by Fanny Waterman and Marion Stein, has been held in the city every three years since 1963 and has launched the careers of many major concert pianists.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds International Concert Season, which includes orchestral and choral concerts in Leeds Town Hall and other events, is the largest local authority music programme in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds International Film Festival is the largest film festival in England outside London and shows films from around the world.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It incorporates the highly successful *Leeds Young People's Film Festival*, which features exciting and innovative films made both for and by children and young people.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Garforth is host to the fortnight-long festival The Garforth Arts Festival which has been an annual event since 2005.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Chapel Allerton Arts Festival is a week-long music and arts event starting in 1998 and held the week after August Bank Holiday each year.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds Festival Fringe is a week long-music festival created in 2010 to showcase local talent in the week prior to Leeds Festival.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Light Night, one of the UK's largest annual arts and light festivals, takes place in the first week of October, turning the entire city into an art installation with light shows, projections, installations and lots more.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Pride is an annual LGBT+ festival held since 2006 supported by the city council and local business.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2018 attendance was 40,000 with over 100 floats and benefits the city by over £3.8 million.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city has a sponsorship scheme for its 15 Rainbow Plaques commemorating places and events that are of significance to the LGBT+ community organised through Leeds Civic Trust.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Other festivals include Transform and Thought Bubble.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In October 1888 Louis Le Prince filmed moving picture sequences *Roundhay Garden Scene* and a *Leeds Bridge* street scene using his single-lens camera and Eastman's paper film.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] These were several years before the work of competing inventors such as Auguste and Louis Lumière and Thomas Edison.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Today, Leeds International Film Festival's International Short Film Competition is named after Louis Le Prince.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The 2015 documentary film *The First Film*, which first aired at the Edinburgh International Film Festival, documents Le Prince's pioneering status.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Wordsworth Donisthorpe who was also from Leeds, filmed the second-oldest-surviving film.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is not known if he and Louis Le Prince ever met but they both had a strong connection to the Leeds Philosophical and Literary Society.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Donisthorpe's patent for a camera to capture the moving image pre dated Le Prince's by twelve years.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a rich film exhibition culture.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In addition to the Leeds International Film Festival and Leeds Young Film Festival, the city hosts numerous independent cinemas and pop-up venues for film screenings.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Cottage Road Cinema and Hyde Park Picture House have continuously been showing films since 1912 and 1914, respectively, which ranks them among the oldest still-running cinemas in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has produced many writers of note, including celebrated author and playwright Alan Bennett.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Tolkien, author of *The Lord of the Rings*, lived and taught in Leeds from 1921 to 1925.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Author Joanne Harris was a teacher at Leeds Grammar School for 15 years, and based several of her novels on her experiences there.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2019 and 2020, Leeds hosted the Leeds Lit Fest, a "non-traditional" literature festival, incorporating talks, panels, and workshops.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are plans to create a National Poetry Centre in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has many large parks and open spaces.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Roundhay Park is the largest park in the city and is one of the largest city parks in Europe.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The park has more than 700 acres (2.8 km2) of parkland, lakes, woodland and gardens which are all owned by Leeds City Council.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are many more smaller parks and open spaces scattered around the city, which make up around 21.7% of the city's total area.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A 2017 survey ranked Leeds 7th among the ten largest UK cities (by population) for the amount of green space, although published comments on the survey pointed out major inconsistencies in the city boundaries used.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] As part of the South Bank regeneration project, plans are in development for Aire Park, a new 3.5 hectare city centre park located close to the former Tetley Brewery site.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Planning permission for the first phase to be undertaken by Vastint UK was granted in December 2018.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2023, the Monk Bridge viaduct was restored by a developer and subsequently opened as the Monk Bridge Viaduct Garden.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is home to the refurbished Grand Theatre where the only national opera company outside London, Opera North, is based.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The City Varieties Music Hall is one of the UK's few remaining music halls, and famously hosted performances by Charlie Chaplin and Harry Houdini.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It was also the venue of the BBC television programme *The Good Old Days*.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The newest theatre, containing two auditoriums, is the Leeds Playhouse, which had formerly been known as the West Yorkshire Playhouse.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Just south of Leeds Bridge once stood The Theatre which hosted Sarah Siddons and Ching Lau Lauro in 1786 and 1834, respectively.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are a number of independent venues in Leeds that host live music.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] For example, the Brudenell Social Club is one of the most popular indie venues in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The First Direct Arena is a 13,500-seater stadium that opened in September 2013, and used for live music events.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Concerts are also held at the O2 Academy, Elland Road, which has hosted groups such as Queen and Kaiser Chiefs, among others and at the universities.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Roundhay Park in north Leeds has seen some of the world's biggest artists including Michael Jackson, Madonna, Bruce Springsteen, and Robbie Williams.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is also home to Phoenix Dance Theatre, who were formed in the Harehills area of the city in 1981, and Northern Ballet Theatre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In autumn 2010 the two companies moved into a purpose-built dance centre which is the largest space for dance outside London.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is also the only space for dance to house a national classical and a national contemporary dance company alongside each another.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A public artwork by Adrian Riley called 'Leeds Song Tunnel' celebrates bands and musical artists who have their origins in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] On Valentine's Day 1970, the Who performed and recorded their album *Live at Leeds* at the University of Leeds Refectory.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Since its initial reception, *Live at Leeds* has been cited by several music critics as the best live rock recording of all time.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Pink Floyd's popular second single "See Emily Play" was written in Leeds in 1967 after a gig in the old Leeds City College Technology Campus, then known as Kitson College.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is the only city outside of London to have its own repertory theatre, ballet, and opera companies.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is Purple Flag accredited to indicate an entertaining, diverse, safe and enjoyable night.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has the fourth largest student population in the country (over 200,000), and is therefore one of the UK's hotspots for night-life.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are a large number of pubs, bars, nightclubs and restaurants, as well as a multitude of venues for live music.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The full range of music tastes is catered for in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It includes the original home of the famous club nights Back 2 Basics, Speedqueen and Vague.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Morley was the location of techno club The Orbit.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The F Club was club night that ran in Leeds between 1977 and 1982 and specialised in punk rock and post-punk.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It would prove highly influential to the development of the goth subculture, due to it leading to the formation of seminal gothic rock bands like The Sisters of Mercy, The March Violets, and Southern Death Cult.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The now-defunct club Le Phonographique was located in the Merrion Centre and was the first gothic nightclub in the world.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a well established LGBT+ nightlife scene, predominantly located in the Freedom Quarter on Lower Briggate.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The New Penny is one of the UK's longest running LGBT+ venues, and Leeds oldest gay bar.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Towards Millennium Square is a growing entertainment district providing for both students and weekend visitors.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The square has many bars and restaurants and a large outdoor screen.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Millennium Square is a venue for large seasonal events such as a Christmas market, gigs and concerts, and citywide parties.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is adjacent to the Mandela Gardens, which were opened by Nelson Mandela in 2001.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] A number of public art features, fountains, and greenery can be found here.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Yorkshire has a great history of real ale, but several bars near the railway station are fusing traditional beers with a modern bar Leeds also hosts an annual Leeds International Beer Festival, held at Leeds Town Hall every September.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a diverse media landscape and is considered a media hub.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Yorkshire Post Newspapers Ltd, owned by National World, is based in the city, and produces a daily morning broadsheet, *The Yorkshire Post*, and an evening paper, the *Yorkshire Evening Post* (YEP).
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The YEP has a website which includes a series of community pages which focus on specific areas of the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The *Wetherby News* covers mainly areas within the north eastern sector of the district, and the *Wharfedale & Airedale Observer*, published in Ilkley, covers the north-west, both appearing weekly.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The two largest universities both have student newspapers, the weekly *Leeds Student* from the University of Leeds and the monthly *The Met* from Leeds Beckett University.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] *The Leeds Guide* was a fortnightly listings magazine, which was established in 1997 and ceased publication in 2012.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Free publications include the *Leeds Weekly News*, produced by Yorkshire Post Newspapers in four geographic versions and distributed to households in the main urban area of the city, and the regional version of *Metro*, which is distributed on buses and at railway stations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] BBC Television and ITV both have regional studios and broadcasting centres in Leeds, while Channel 4 opened a new headquarters at the Majestic in 2020.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] ITV Yorkshire, formerly Yorkshire Television, broadcasts from the Leeds Studios on Kirkstall Road.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are a number of independent film production companies, including the not-for-profit cooperative Leeds Animation Workshop, founded in 1978; community video producers Vera Media and several small commercial production companies.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] BBC Radio Leeds, Hits Radio West Yorkshire, Greatest Hits Radio West Yorkshire, Capital Yorkshire, and Heart Yorkshire broadcast from the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] LSRfm.com is based in Leeds University Union, and regularly hosts outside broadcasts around the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Many communities within Leeds now have their own local radio stations, such as East Leeds FM and Tempo FM for Wetherby and the surrounding areas.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a local television station called Leeds TV which is required to broadcast 37 hours a week of first-run local programming.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The station had launched in 2014 as *Made in Leeds* which launched across the city in 2014.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The city has teams representing all the major national sports.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds United F.C. is the city's main football club, additional clubs include Guiseley AFC, Farsley Celtic, and Garforth Town.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds United was formed in 1919 and plays at the 37,890-capacity Elland Road Stadium in Beeston.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The team rejoined the Premier League, following a sixteen-year stint in lower divisions, after they won promotion by winning the EFL Championship in 2019–20, but in the Premier League Season of 2022–23 they got relegated to the Championship again.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] After winning the 2024–25 Championship League, they have once again been promoted to the Premier League.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Guiseley was formed in 1909 and plays at the 4,000 capacity Nethermoor Park Stadium in Guiseley; the team plays in the Northern Premier League.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Farsley Celtic was formed in 1908 and plays in the National League North and their stadium is Throstle Nest.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Garforth Town was formed in 1964 and plays in the Northern Counties East League Premier Division; their stadium is Wheatley Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Rhinos are the most successful rugby league team in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 2009, they became first club to be Super League champions three seasons running, giving them their fourth Super League title.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] They play their home games at the Headingley Rugby Stadium.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Hunslet, based at the John Charles Centre for Sport, play in the Co-Operative Championship One.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] East Leeds and Oulton Raiders play in the National Conference League.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Bramley Buffaloes (previously Bramley), and Leeds Akkies were members of the Rugby League Conference.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds Tykes were the foremost rugby union team in Leeds and they previously also played at Headingley.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] They play in National League 1 having been relegated from RFU Championship at the end of the 2019–20 season.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Otley RUFC are a rugby union club based to the north of the city and compete in National League 2 North, whilst Morley RFC, located in Morley currently play in National Division Three North.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Headingley Cricket Stadium is home to Yorkshire County Cricket Club which is the most successful cricket team in England, with 33 County Championship wins (including one shared).
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds City Athletic Club competes in the British Athletics League and UK Women's League as well as the Northern Athletics League.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is home to a number of field hockey clubs that compete in the Men's England Hockey League, the Women's England Hockey League, the North Hockey League, the Yorkshire Hockey Association League and the BUCS leagues.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] These include Leeds Hockey Club, Leeds Adel Carnegie Hockey Club, the University of Leeds Hockey Club, and Leeds Beckett University Hockey Club.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The City of Leeds Synchronised Swimming Club train at the John Charles Centre for Sport and are represented by swimmers throughout the whole of the North East.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The club was founded in 2008 and only compete in National and International Competition.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Other facilities include the Leeds Wall (climbing) and Yeadon Tarn sailing centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In 1929 the first Ryder Cup of Golf to be held on British soil was competed for at Moortown Golf Club in Alwoodley, and Wetherby has a National Hunt racecourse.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In the period 1928 to 1939 speedway racing was staged in Leeds on a track at the greyhound stadium known as Fullerton Park, adjacent to Elland Road.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The track entered a team in the 1931 Northern league.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The 2014 Tour de France Grand Départ took place from the Headrow in Leeds city centre on 5 July 2014.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds is well known for its divers and features some of the best diving facilities in the UK.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has an ice hockey team, the Leeds Knights (formerly named Leeds Chiefs); they play at the Planet Ice Arena in Beeston, Leeds, in the National Ice Hockey League.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a well-established climbing and mountaineering scene.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Yorkshire Ramblers' Club, England's second oldest mountaineering club, was founded in Headingley in 1892, and the city is also home to a number of other climbing clubs and venues.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The UK's first artificial climbing wall for training and developing technique was established at the University of Leeds in 1964.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has hosted the BMC's British Bouldering Championships, and the Youth Climbing Series Grand Final.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The majority of people in Leeds identify themselves as Christians.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds does not have a Church of England cathedral: although it is in the Anglican Diocese of Leeds (formerly in the Diocese of Ripon and Leeds), headed by the Bishop of Leeds, the diocese has cathedrals in Bradford, Ripon, and Wakefield (although the Bishop's residence has been in Leeds since 2008).
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The most important Anglican church is Leeds Minster, although St.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] George's has the largest congregation by far.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds has a Roman Catholic Cathedral, the episcopal seat of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The proportion of Muslims in Leeds is slightly above average for the country (5.4% as of 2011).
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Mosques can be found throughout the city, serving Muslim communities in Chapeltown, Harehills, Hyde Park and parts of Beeston.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The largest mosque is Leeds Grand Mosque in Hyde Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Sikh community is represented by gurdwaras (temples) spread across the city, the largest being in Chapeltown.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There is also a colourful religious annual procession, called the Nagar Kirtan, into Millennium Square in the city centre on 13–14 April to celebrate Vaisakhi—the Sikh New Year and the birth of the religion.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It is estimated that around 3,000 Sikhs in Leeds take part in this annual event.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Jewish community of Leeds is the third-largest in the United Kingdom, after London and Greater Manchester.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The areas of Alwoodley and Moortown contain sizeable Jewish populations.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are eight active synagogues in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Hindu community in Leeds has a temple (mandir) at Hyde Park.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The temple has all the major Hindu deities and is dedicated to the Lord Mahavira of the Jains.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Various Buddhist traditions are represented in Leeds, including: Soka Gakkai, Theravada, Tibetan, Triratna Buddhist Community, and Zen.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Buddhist community (sangha) comes together to celebrate the major festival of Wesak in May.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There is also a community of the Baháʼí Faith in Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Water supply and sewerage services in Leeds are provided by Yorkshire Water, part of the Kelda Group.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Prior to 1973 water and sewerage services had been provided by the Leeds Corporation.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds City Council has a target of 11MW of renewable energy from onshore wind by 2010 and an aspirational target of 75MW by 2020.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] There are currently no operational wind farms in Leeds, but a planning application by Banks Renewables Ltd for five turbines at Hook Moor, near Micklefield, was approved in 2011.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The area is policed by the West Yorkshire Police.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The force has five policing districts covering the West Yorkshire area, one of which covers Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds District Headquarters is located at Elland Road in the south of the city.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] In the north-west of the city the main stations are Weetwood and Woodhouse Lane; in the north-east, the main stations are Stainbeck near Chapel Allerton and Killingbeck; in the south the main stations are Leeds Central, located on Park Street in the city centre, and the District Headquarters itself.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Fire and rescue services are provided by the West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The fire stations in Leeds are: Cookridge, Gipton, Hunslet, Stanks, Moortown, Stanningley, and the "Leeds" fire station (near the city centre, on Kirkstall Road).
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] NHS health services are provided by the Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, Leeds Primary Care Trust, and Leeds and York Partnership NHS Foundation Trust, which provides mental health services.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds General Infirmary ("LGI") is a listed building with more recent additions and is in the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] St James's University Hospital, known locally as "Jimmy's", is to the north east of the city centre and is the largest teaching hospital in Europe.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Other NHS hospitals are Chapel Allerton Hospital, Seacroft Hospital, Wharfedale Hospital in Otley, and Leeds Dental Institute.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] West Yorkshire Joint Services provides analytical, archaeological, archives, ecology, materials testing, and trading standards services in Leeds and the other four districts of West Yorkshire.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] It was created following the abolition of the county council in 1986 and expanded in 1997, and is funded by the five district councils, pro rata to their population.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The Leeds site of the archives service is in the former public library at Sheepscar, Leeds.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] Leeds City Council is responsible for over 50 public libraries across the whole city, including 5 mobile libraries.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The main Central Library is located on the Headrow, in the city centre.
[src:leeds/leeds-p02] The following people, military units and organisations and groups have received the Freedom of the City of Leeds.
